headline: Georgia-Pacific
abstract: LEAD: The Georgia-Pacific Corporation, which last week offered to buy the Great Northern Nekoosa Corporation for $3.1 billion, said the Interstate Commerce Commission would allow it to proceed with the proposed acquisition. The deal would create the nation's largest forest-products company. Nekoosa, based in Norwalk, Conn., has not responded formally to the bid.

headline: MARKET RECOVERS HALF OF ITS LOSSES, LED BY BLUE CHIPS
abstract: LEAD: The stock market overcame a shaky opening yesterday and roared back on heavy volume to regain about half the losses recorded in the heavy selling late Friday.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  COMPANIES  Mitsubishi Estate bought 51 percent of the Rockefeller Group, which owns Rockefeller Center, the Radio City Music Hall and other mid-Manhattan office buildings, for $846 million in cash.  [ Page A1. ]  The Rockefeller Group quickly turned to Mitsubishi Estate when it sought a prestigious buyer.

headline: Anne Frank Benefactor Hailed
abstract: LEAD: West Germany has awarded its highest civilian medal to a Dutch woman who hid Anne Frank from the Nazis, the West German Embassy said today. The woman, Miep Gies, is being given the Federal Cross of Merit First Class for her ''crucial role'' in hiding Miss Frank and her family, the embassy said. Mrs.

headline: Yugoslav Police Check Cars To Stop Protest by Serbians
abstract: LEAD: The police checked vehicles today to stop Serbians from reaching Ljubljana in spite of an order banning a mass protest.

headline: Profits of Gannett Rose By 11% in Third Quarter
abstract: LEAD: The Gannett Company said yesterday that lower newsprint costs and cost controls at its USA Today newspaper helped profits rise 11 percent in the third quarter.

headline: Crosman Products Sold for $41 Million
abstract: LEAD: Crosman Products Inc., an air gun maker, is being sold to Hicks, Muse & Company and an investor group for $41 million in cash, the Dallas-based investment group said. Crosman, based in East Bloomfield, N.Y., was a division of the Coleman Companies, which was recently acquired by McAndrews & Forbes.

headline: Chile Is Getting Independent Central Bank
abstract: LEAD: In the first attempt in Latin America to free a central bank from Government control, Chile's central bank will begin functioning autonomously on Monday under a five-member board. The governing panel was named last week in a surprisingly harmonious agreement between the departing Government of Gen.

headline: Beijing Welcomes 'Old Friend' Nixon, Hoping for Thaw With U.S.
abstract: LEAD: Former President Richard M. Nixon arrived today for a visit of about six days in which he will meet with top Chinese leaders, and although it is billed as an unofficial fact-finding trip, both the United States and China seem to hope that it will help smooth relations.

headline: Domestic Car Sales Show Drop
abstract: LEAD: The nation's Big Three auto makers suffered serious sales declines in mid-November, while the so-called Japanese transplants posted sharp gains on far fewer sales. Over all, sales of domestically produced cars slumped 6.1 percent, and light-truck sales dropped 1.7 percent, not quite so dismal a trend as during the early part of the month.

headline: Developer Transforms A Factory in Jersey City
abstract: LEAD: Two 150-foot-high smokestacks that tower over the Van Vorst historic district in Jersey City mark the site of the former Joseph Dixon Crucible Company factory at Wayne and Varick Streets, a maze of cavernous buildings where crucibles, pencils, crayons, stove polish, lubricants and other products were once made.

headline: Lebanese Peace Talks Stall Over Syrians
abstract: LEAD: A peace conference in the Saudi city of Taif was deadlocked today over a timetable for the withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING; Texas Banks In Consumer Campaigns
abstract: LEAD: IN the good old days in Texas, when the banking business and big-money commercial lending were virtually synonymous, the common man and his common checking account attracted little attention and few advertising dollars.

headline: Eastern Europe's Lures and Hurdles
abstract: LEAD: American businesses are rushing to Eastern Europe with visions of tapping new markets for consumers and developing low-cost manufacturing bases, but experts on the region warn that formidable obstacles remain.

headline: Panamanian Resistance To U.S. Virtually at End
abstract: LEAD: With Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in the Vatican mission and trying to negotiate safe departure from the country, resistance to American forces virtually collapsed today. An American spokesman said the general's move to seek asylum was ''a major victory'' for the United States.

headline: Yields on C.D.'s Decline
abstract: LEAD: Yields offered for certificates of deposit and money market accounts at commercial banks and savings institutions were down for the week ended yesterday.

headline: Ex-Quintus Executive in High Intergraph Job
abstract: LEAD: The Intergraph Corporation, a software company in Huntsville, Ala., announced yesterday that James W. Meadlock, the company's president and chairman, had been promoted to the new position of chief executive.

headline: In Japan, It's Costly to Be a Consumer
abstract: LEAD: Japanese consumers are paying about twice as much as Americans for electric shavers, floppy disk drives and camera lenses and three and a half times as much for spark plugs, a survey conducted by Japanese and American Government agencies showed today.

headline: Dow Ends 3.69 Lower In Wild Day
abstract: LEAD: The stock market fluctuated wildly yesterday on heavy volume. The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 85 points in the first hour of trading but recovered in the late afternoon to close only 3.69 points lower, at 2,659.22.

headline: Pharmacies Fight Off New Competition
abstract: LEAD: There is a drug war in America today that has nothing to do with crack dens and money laundering. Pharmacies are fighting to keep what was once their exclusive domain: the retail market for prescription drugs. Since 1985, health maintenance organizations, doctors and mail-order houses have cornered a growing share of that business and last year sold 15 percent of the nation's $28 billion in prescription drugs.

headline: Upheaval in the East: The Countryside; Snipers in a Steeple: The Carnage Shocks Rumanian Village
abstract: LEAD: Blood stains the steps of the church of this border town in the southern Rumanian farmlands.

headline: U.S. Contractor Cites 2 Officials In a Guilty Plea
abstract: LEAD: The long-running inquiry into Pentagon fraud edged closer to former senior Defense Department officials today when a New York military contracting company admitted in court that it had illegally obtained inside purchasing information from the Navy and Air Force.

headline: Farm Co-op Income Up
abstract: LEAD: The Agriculture Department said today that the net income of farm cooperatives last year rose to nearly $1.7 billion, continuing a rebound from the sharp declines of the mid-1980's. Combined business volume of cooperatives in 1988 was reported at $66.3 billion, up 10.3 percent from $60.2 billion in 1987.

headline: Division Over Mexico Economic Plan
abstract: LEAD: Elated and hopeful when President Carlos Salinas de Gortari took office a year ago this month, the leaders of Mexico's private sector now find themselves seriously divided over the extent to which they should support and cooperate with the Government's changes of the Mexican economy.

headline: Debate Begins on Reducing Budget Deficit
abstract: LEAD: House and Senate budget negotiators today began what promises to be a slow process: reconciling major differences in their plans for reducing the fiscal year 1990 budget deficit and repealing $16.1 billion in automatic spending cuts that took effect on Monday.

headline: Bulova Seeking to Take The Watch Beyond Time
abstract: LEAD: The Bulova Corporation has a new face, indeed a variety of new faces -15 original one-inch-square geometric designs by Victor Vasarely, the French painter who is known as the father of ''Op Art.''

headline: NATO Plans New Mix If Deep Cuts Are Made
abstract: LEAD: The commander of NATO forces in Europe says he has begun to consider new military plans for the defense of Western Europe in the event that deep cuts are made in conventional forces.

headline: PANAMA SHOOTING CONDEMNED BY U.S.
abstract: LEAD: The Bush Administration said today that the shooting of an unarmed American army officer by Panamanian soldiers Saturday night was part of a pattern of ''aggression'' by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and that Washington would not rule out a military response.

headline: Czech Communist Party Struggling to Stay Calm
abstract: LEAD: In the face of widespread protest and with the threat of a new general strike, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia is seeking to stave off disarray and panic among its members and leaders.

headline: Phoenix Technologies Appoints Top Officer
abstract: LEAD: Phoenix Technologies Ltd., a software development company, yesterday named Ronald D. Fisher as its president and chief executive.

headline: As Westmark Divests, Its Chairman Resigns
abstract: LEAD: Adm. Bobby R. Inman has resigned as chairman, president and chief executive of Westmark Systems Inc. and its subsidiary, Tracor Holdings Inc., effective Dec. 31.

headline: Wickes to Sell Car Parts Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Wickes Companies said it had agreed to sell A.P.S. Inc., a distributor of automotive parts, for $200 million to a company organized by the management-buyout firm of Clayton & Dubilier Inc.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: More Antitrust Challenges Are Expected Under Bush
abstract: LEAD: The Bush Administration will be challenging many more large mergers and suing more companies for false advertising than the Reagan Administration did, Administration officials and antitrust experts are predicting.

headline: People
abstract: LEAD: * Robert E. Hall has been named senior vice president of J. Walter Thompson/Chicago.

headline: Trump Scraps Shuttle Ads
abstract: LEAD: Donald J. Trump has lived up to his self-proclaimed reputation as a temperamental client, scrapping the new advertising campaign for the Trump Shuttle after publicly deriding it earlier this week.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Pro Bono
abstract: LEAD: * Leo Burnett U.S.A. has created a pro bono ad campaign to heighten awareness of Alzheimer's disease. It will run in November, which is National Alzheimer's Month.

headline: PLANE IN SALVADOR WITH SOVIET ARMS CRASHES AND 4 DIE
abstract: LEAD: A light plane carrying two dozen Soviet-made antiaircraft missiles crashed in eastern El Salvador today on what Government officials said was a mission to resupply leftist guerrillas here with weapons from Nicaragua.

headline: Service for Alvin Ailey
abstract: LEAD: A memorial service for Alvin Ailey, founder and director of the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater, will be held on Friday at 10:30 A.M. at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, 112th Street and Amsterdam Avenue. Mr. Ailey died of a blood disorder last Friday at the age of 58.

headline: ABC Seeks Court Order To Show Cuban Games
abstract: LEAD: Capital Cities/ABC Inc. yesterday asked a Federal District Court in Manhattan to order the Government to allow ABC Sports to televise the 1991 Pan American Games from Havana.

headline: Election in Namibia Worries Whites
abstract: LEAD: As the elections held this week bring home the prospect of black majority rule for Namibia, the white inhabitants of this northern mining town are worried.

headline: People
abstract: LEAD: * Linda Clasen has been appointed creative director of Gregory & Clyburne.

headline: Patents; New Method To Cultivate A Mushroom
abstract: LEAD: The Campbell Soup Company obtained a patent this week on a new method of growing the shiitake mushroom, which is immensely popular in Japan and China and until recently has been usually grown inside oak logs.

headline: Oil Stockpile Discussions
abstract: LEAD: A team of experts from the United States will tour the Persian Gulf next week to discuss how the big oil states in the region could contribute to the United States Strategic Petroleum Reserve.

headline: U.S. Securities Prices Are Mixed
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds were narrowly mixed in slow trading yesterday.

headline: Fighting in Panama: The Search; Hundreds of Tips but Still no Noriega
abstract: LEAD: Early Wednesday morning, American special-operation forces equipped with night-vision devices, stun grenades and customized submachine guns struck seven sites around Panama where intelligence information indicated that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega might be staying, Pentagon officials said today.

headline: Agreement Is Reached at the U.N. To End Use of Drift Fishing Nets
abstract: LEAD: After difficult negotiations that have pitted the United States against Japan for the first time at the United Nations, an agreement has been reached on steps to end the use of huge fishing nets 30 or more miles in length, that can sweep whole ocean areas free of marine life.

headline: U.S. Medical Workers Seized in Mozambique
abstract: LEAD: Government soldiers seized six members of an American medical team and two South African colleagues and held them at a military compound in northern Mozambique, United States officials said today.

headline: BONN OUTLINES AID FOR EAST GERMANY
abstract: LEAD: West Germany made public the outlines of a possible economic aid program to East Germany today, but repeated a warning that the proposal would be adopted only if East Germany carried out a ''thorough change'' of its centralized economy and spelled out the changes it plans.

headline: Money Fund Assets Up
abstract: LEAD: The assets of the nation's 476 money market mutual funds increased by $2.19 billion, to $359.71 billion, for the week that ended Wednesday, the Investment Company Institute said yesterday. The assets of the 143 institutional funds decreased by $6.7 million, to $84.82 billion. The assets of the 236 general-purpose funds were up by $750.5 million, to $117.66 billion.

headline: Batco Closing Factories
abstract: LEAD: The British American Tobacco Company, a unit of B.A.T. Industries P.L.C., said today that it would close cigarette factories in Liverpool in northwest England and in Amsterdam. A total of 599 jobs will be lost.

headline: Assets Drop At Savings Institutions
abstract: LEAD: The assets of the nation's savings and loan institutions continued to shrink significantly in September in preparation for tough financial standards that take effect next week, the Government said today.

headline: Frito to Tracy-Locke
abstract: LEAD: Frito-Lay Inc. awarded its regional advertising and marketing accounts last week to Tracy-Locke, a Dallas agency and subsidiary of the Omnicom Group. A Frito-Lay spokeswoman declined to give the budget of the account, but said that the company would channel more of its overall marketing budget into regional promotions.

headline: Warsaw Pact Condemns '68 Prague Invasion
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union and four Warsaw Pact allies made a common break with the past today by jointly condemning the Soviet-led 1968 military suppression of the Czechoslovak experiment in political liberalization called the Prague Spring.

headline: U.S. Threatens to Quit U.N. Unit
abstract: LEAD: The United States has warned that it may pull out of the United Nations Food and Agricultural Organization if the agency extends any new measure of recognition to the Palestine Liberation Organization.

headline: National Education Is Expecting Loss
abstract: LEAD: The National Education Corporation said it expected to report a loss in the third quarter of about $6 million. The education training company, based in Irvine, Calif., attributed the expected loss to disappointing revenues at its Applied Learning division, a computer training concern. The company said its fourth-quarter revenues at Applied

headline: Next Inc. Is Offering Improvements in Its Work Station
abstract: LEAD: Next Inc., the company founded in 1986 by Steven P. Jobs, the former chairman of Apple Computer Inc., announced two significant developments yesterday. It said that it would add an accelerator to its computer work station to resolve complaints about slow performance and that it would offer a lower-cost version of the work station for use on computer networks.

headline: Patents; Synthetic Blood
abstract: LEAD: Motivated in part by the danger of transmitting contagious diseases through blood transfusions, as well as by periodic scarcities in supplies, two chemists have patented a synthetic blood. The blood consists of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, encapsulated in bubbles that have the consistency of Jell-O.

headline: Heck's in Deal With Jordache
abstract: LEAD: Unable to turn a profit despite emerging from Federal bankruptcy court protection, Heck's Inc. announced plans to sell its retail operations, consisting of 55 discount stores in six states, to New York-based Jordache Enterprises Inc.Heck's is essentially giving away its retailers to a subsidiary of Jordache, which will assume the chain's debts and long-term obligations, said Maartan Hemsley,

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  The Economy

headline: More Sway for Noriega IS Expected in Panama
abstract: LEAD: The National Assembly convened for a second day today with members saying they planned to vote Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega head of Government.

headline: Wall Street Trader Stays Cool During a Weekend of Anxiety
abstract: LEAD: William Silver, a quick-witted trader on the American Stock Exchange, is reasonably confident that the performance of the financial markets today will not match the collapse of Monday, Oct. 19, 1987.

headline: Drug Trafficker's Death Cheers Many Colombians
abstract: LEAD: A wave of euphoria swept across Colombia today in the aftermath of the killing by security forces of a powerful drug trafficker accused of directing a four-month terror campaign.

headline: A Proposal to Revamp And Buy Sharon Steel
abstract: LEAD: Two investment concerns said yesterday that they would sponsor a reorganization plan to bring the Sharon Steel Corporation out of bankruptcy.

headline: Ecolab Revamping May Be Discussed
abstract: LEAD: Southeastern Asset Management Inc., a Memphis-based investment advisory concern that holds a 12.1 percent stake in Ecolab Inc., said it had been approached by third parties interested in discussing a possible revamping of the St. Paul-based cleaning and maintenance company. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Southeastern Asset said it ''may engage in such discussions with third parties.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESST: Television; The Networks' 'Opportunity' in Sony Deal
abstract: LEAD: A BAD joke in Hollywood last week suggested that Columbia television had started pitching a series to the networks based on the film ''Tora, Tora, Tora.'' That film tells the story of the Pearl Harbor attack from the Japanese point of view.

headline: Moody's Lowers Ratings On Debt of Massachusetts
abstract: LEAD: The ratings on as much as $8.5 billion in Massachusetts debt have been reduced by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and the Standard & Poor's Corporation placed the state under review for possible downgrading.

headline: Loral to Acquire Honeywell Unit
abstract: LEAD: Honeywell Inc. said it had agreed to sell its Electro-Optics division to the Loral Corporation, a New York military electronics company, for undisclosed terms.

headline: Diligent Enemy of Apartheid
abstract: LEAD: Walter Sisulu said he never despaired in prison, convinced that ''sooner or later they would have to cave in.'' Man in the News, page A6.

headline: Cautious Slovaks Yearn for a Bit of Breathing Room
abstract: LEAD: Unlike their Czech countrymen in Prague, 175 miles to the northwest, few Slovaks in this city of 500,000 on the Danube rushed into the streets singing and dancing last night when the resignation of the party leadership was announced.

headline: Wang Agreement On Selling Assets
abstract: LEAD: Wang Laboratories Inc. said it had agreed in principle to sell $200 million of nonstrategic assets as part of its continuing drive to reduce debt and return to profitability. Richard Miller, president of the Lowell-based computer maker, said the nonstrategic assets include the company's lease portfolio, money credit operations and a manufacturing plant in

headline: Summit Bid By Venezuela
abstract: LEAD: Venezuela's President, Carlos Andres Perez, is calling for a special summit meeting of rich and poor countries to tackle the crippling debt and other economic problems of South American nations.

headline: Upheaval in the East; King Michael Ready to Return to Rumania
abstract: LEAD: King Michael, the exiled Rumanian monarch, said today that he was ready to return to his country as head of a constitutional monarchy ''if the people want me to come back.''

headline: Exxon Plant Shut
abstract: LEAD: The explosion Sunday at the Exxon Corporation's refinery in Baton Rouge, La., has forced an adjacent Exxon chemical unit to suspend production, company officials said. The chemical plant, though undamaged by the explosion and subsequent fire, uses naphtha from the refinery to produce compounds like propylene and benzene.

headline: The Fall of Gandhi; Nehru's Grandson, Many Indians Say, Was Never Quite One of the People
abstract: LEAD: When Rajiv Gandhi went to the President on this cool, clear morning to resign as Prime Minister of India, he was in almost every sense a man alone. The defeat of the grandson of Jawaharlal Nehru was a personal defeat.

headline: U.S. Role Seen on Japan Jets
abstract: LEAD: Two leading American companies have accepted an invitation from the Japanese Government to participate in a $195 million project to develop jet engines for supersonic passenger aircraft, industry sources said.

headline: Clamor in the East; Amid Hope in Bulgaria, Old Ways May Die Hard
abstract: LEAD: As Bulgaria's National Assembly went through the motions on Friday of naming a president, one lawmaker stood up to praise the preordained choice, Petar Mladenov, the new Communist Party leader.

headline: Fannie Mae Rates Set on Debentures
abstract: LEAD: The Federal National Mortgage Association, known as Fannie Mae, yesterday announced the interest rates for a two-part debenture offering totaling $2 billion.

headline: Palme Conviction Upset; Drifter Is Freed
abstract: LEAD: A seven-member Swedish appeals court today unanimously overturned the conviction of the 42-year-old drifter and drug addict who had been found guilty of the 1986 murder of Prime Minister Olof Palme, and ordered him to be released immediately.

headline: Trump Says He May Seek Retail Chain
abstract: LEAD: Donald J. Trump, the developer, said yesterday that he was talking to the Campeau Corporation about a possible bid for Bloomingdale's, ''but it looks like nothing will materialize because of the short lease on Bloomingdale's flagship store with no options to renew.''

headline: A Japanese Strategy for Boeing
abstract: LEAD: The Boeing Company, once fiercely independent and self-reliant, is turning to partnerships with the Japanese in the belief that there is no better way to preserve its position as the world's leading aircraft manufacturer. But the emerging alliance is not without a conflict: while the Japanese try to learn everything they can about making airplanes,

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING; Prudential Finalists
abstract: LEAD: Backer Spielvogel Bates dodged a bullet on Friday, surviving another round of cuts on Friday in the competition for the giant Prudential Insurance Company advertising account. BSB, the incumbent agency, joined Grey Advertising; Scali, McCabe, Sloves; and Lowe Marschalk as finalists for the account, which is worth more than $60 million.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Asher/Gould Sees Suzuki Opportunities
abstract: LEAD: ASHER/GOULD, a medium-size Los Angeles ad agency, has had a fair amount of experience with clients whose public image is less than stellar. Among its biggest accounts is the American Savings and Loan Association; until the completion of a Federal bailout plan at the end of last year, it was the nation's largest insolvent savings institution.

headline: U.S.-Soviet-Chinese Teams Will Jointly Attempt Everest
abstract: LEAD: Teams from China, the Soviet Union and the United States will attempt to scale Mount Everest together next year to draw attention to international cooperation and problems of the environment.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Babcock Industries, Fairfield, Conn., an industrial and consumer-products manufacturer, said Dennis F. Flint had been named deputy group chief executive of its parent company, FKI Babcock P.L.C., Halifax, England.

headline: OPEC Study Of East Bloc
abstract: LEAD: OPEC is studying the effect that the upheaval in Eastern European countries could have on their demand for oil, most of which is now supplied by the Soviet Union, OPEC officials said today.

headline: SCI Television In Loan Default
abstract: LEAD: SCI Television Inc. said yesterday that as expected it had defaulted on a $153 million principal payment that it owes a group of bank lenders, led by the Bankers Trust Company, and would also have to skip interest payments due Oct. 15 on two ''junk bond'' issues.

headline: Pretoria Playing Down Namibia 'Infiltration'
abstract: LEAD: The South African Government moved today to play down Foreign Minister Roelof F. Botha's contention on Wednesday that hundreds of black nationalist guerrillas were infiltrating into Namibia in advance of elections next week.

headline: 200 Military Officers Are Pardoned in Argentina
abstract: LEAD: President Carlos Saul Menem today pardoned more than 200 military officers accused of human rights abuses and aiding military rebellions, saying the move was essential for national reconciliation.

headline: Thailand Bans Asian Journal
abstract: LEAD: The police said today that they were banning local distribution of The Asian Wall Street Journal because of an article that they said had insulted the leader of Thailand's predominant Buddhist faith.

headline: How Taiwan Wins Friends and Miffs Beijing
abstract: LEAD: Armed with a new flexibility and immense reservoirs of foreign exchange, Taiwan is struggling for a seat at the international table, and in the process new tensions are surfacing between the rival Governments in Taipei and Beijing.

headline: Site of Golden Horse Is No Longer a Puzzle
abstract: LEAD: The mystery of the golden horse has been solved.

headline: Bush Asks Aquino to Insure Safety of Americans
abstract: LEAD: President Bush called President Corazon C. Aquino of the Philippines tonight to express concern for the safety of some 200 United States citizens trapped in Manila hotels occupied by rebel soldiers, a White House official said.

headline: BRAZIL WILL VOTE WITH EYE ON ARMY
abstract: LEAD: As campaigning in Brazil's presidential race ended today with the two candidates tied in opinion polls, attention swiveled to the traditional arbiter of Brazilian politics, the military.

headline: Bond Corp. Trading Halted
abstract: LEAD: Alan Bond, the Australian entrepreneur, suffered a double blow today that left his companies' debt downgraded and their shares suspended.

headline: West Bank Arabs Keep a Court System Intact
abstract: LEAD: Chief Justice Khalil Silwani drives to Ramallah every morning, into ''the center of the intifada,'' as he likes to put it, and prepares to preside over cases brought before the Supreme Court for the West Bank - if ever a case is presented.

headline: About Real Estate; More Development on Palisades Site
abstract: LEAD: It has been 18 years since the Palisades Amusement Park in New Jersey closed after its purchase by the Centex Corporation of Dallas, but redevelopment of the 38-acre site atop the Palisades is still going on.

headline: House Rejects Curb on Salvador Aid
abstract: LEAD: Heeding an appeal from President Bush, the House of Representatives today rejected Democratic efforts to restrict aid to El Salvador. But legislators warned that aid would be cut next year if the Salvadoran Government does not arrest and prosecute those responsible for the killings of six Jesuit priests last week.

headline: Upheaval in the East: Victims; For the Victims in Rumania, Flowers and Places of Honor
abstract: LEAD: The bodies came, one by one, to Belu Cemetery today.

headline: Security Pacific In Deal for La Jolla
abstract: LEAD: The Security Pacific Corporation signed a letter of intent to acquire the La Jolla Bancorp in a deal worth about $111 million. Security Pacific said it would pay $15 in Security Pacific stock for each share of La Jolla, whose stock jumped $3 a share, to $13, on the American Stock Exchange. Its 30 percent gain was the best of the day.

headline: Rome Journal; They Came, They Saw, Then They Sandblasted
abstract: LEAD: This capital remains, of course, one of the world's great beauties, but it is hiding many of its charms these days behind veils.

headline: CAN CAPITAL FROM WALL STREET BUOY MINORITY VENTURE POOLS?
abstract: LEAD: A vital source of venture capital for minority companies is shrinking. Minority Enterprise Small Business Investment Companies, which lend to and invest in minority-owned ventures with money raised from private investors and borrowed from the Small Business Administration, have invested a total of more than $750 million in nearly 9,000 companies since 1978, including the buyout of McCall Pattern Company by Reginald Lewis and, more recently, Emerge, a black magazine that made its debut in

headline: Braniff Adviser
abstract: LEAD: Braniff Inc. the financially troubled airline, said it had hired Merrill Lynch to explore the possible sale of the airline. In late September, Braniff filed for protecion from creditors under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act. It was the airline's second such filing in seven years.

headline: Lockheed Reports Loss
abstract: LEAD: The Lockheed Corporation said today that it lost $32 million in the third quarter after taking a $165 million charge to cover cost overruns on several development contracts. The loss was $3 million less than the company predicted last week, when it disclosed the write-off.

headline: CLAMOR IN THE EAST: Goals of the Newcomers; A Search for Work and for Housing As the Emigres Get Their Bearings
abstract: LEAD: There were no speeches, champagne or applause at Bonn-Beuel station this morning, just cups of hot coffee handed out by Red Cross volunteers to revive the tired bodies of some 900 East Germans who traveled here overnight from Czecholovakia.

headline: U.S. Offers to Sell China Million Tons of Subsidized Wheat
abstract: LEAD: The United States offered today to sell one million metric tons of subsidized wheat to China in what would be the first such sale since China's army crushed a pro-democracy movement in June.

headline: Upheaval in the East; In a School, Revolution's Workshop
abstract: LEAD: For the students of the Higher School of Applied Arts, the nationwide student strike that began on Nov. 20 has meant nothing but work, and they love it.

headline: Hershey-Ronzoni
abstract: LEAD: The Hershey Foods Corporation confirmed that it had tentatively agreed to acquire the Ronzoni Foods Corporation, an important expansion of Hershey's pasta business, which is No. 2 in the industry. Hershey, which had previously said it was negotiating the purchase, would not disclose the tentative purchase price of Ronzoni, a part of Kraft General Foods, a unit of Philip Morris Companies.

headline: Home From Salvador, Freed American Is Bitter
abstract: LEAD: The American woman deported from El Salvador after being freed from charges of hiding arms and ammunition for leftist rebels arrived in New York yesterday and harshly criticized the Bush Administration for not presuming her innocence.

headline: Creditors Question Eastern
abstract: LEAD: The unsecured creditors of Eastern Airlines voted unanimously at their meeting Tuesday to have their own financial advisers examine alternative approaches to the airline's plans for its emergence from bankruptcy. That could lead to the creditors' considering presenting their own plan to the court, people who were told of the results of the meeting said yesterday.

headline: Market Place; A Rally in Notes Backed by Assets
abstract: LEAD: DECEMBER has been a profitable month in the small but growing market for asset-backed securities, where institutional investors trade notes backed by consumer loans. After absorbing a two-month glut of new issues, the market staged a year-end rally that brought yields down and raised note prices.

headline: Money Fund Assets Up
abstract: LEAD: The assets of the nation's 478 money market mutual funds increased by $4.65 billion, to $368.27 billion, for the week ended Tuesday, the Investment Company Institute said yesterday. The assets of the 146 institutional funds increased by $2.19 billion, to $89.62 billion. The assets of the 235 general-purpose funds were up by $737.4 million, to $119.53 billion.

headline: Secret Beijing Report Assails Ousted Party Leader
abstract: LEAD: A secret Government report has been issued bitterly attacking the ousted Communist Party leader, Zhao Ziyang, for economic mismanagement. It is a new step in the campaign to hold Mr. Zhao responsible for China's economic and political problems.

headline: Book Industry's Confidence Hurt by Shake-Ups and Cuts
abstract: LEAD: For the first time within decades, the book industry is beset by a crisis of confidence. headline: Economic Scene; Reality's the Thing This Field Needs

abstract: LEAD: The Guber-Peters Entertainment Company said yesterday that its net income for the three months ended Aug. 31 was $5.8 million, or 50 cents a share, compared with a loss of $6.9 million a year earlier. The current figures reflect an extraordinary gain of $2.1 million after taxes from the repurchase at a discount of a $9.9 million principal amount of the company's outstanding convertible debentures.

abstract: LEAD: Seasoned party bosses who have dominated Indian politics for decades have a new task in 1989. They must compete for the votes of a new electorate of 35 million or more voters from 18 to 21 years of age, enfranchised under a law passed this year.

abstract: LEAD: Sometimes one does not know whether to laugh or rail at the gullibility of Congress, and the hypocrisy of Wall Street.

Every plant of the more than 100 ordered since 1973 has been canceled, and many others are approaching retirement. But reactor manufacturers say that fears of global warming - the greenhouse effect - are giving them a second chance.

headline: Morocco Trade Deficit
abstract: LEAD: Morocco's trade deficit grew more than 60 percent in the first half of this year, according to official figures published today. Officials attributed the increase to costlier oil and wheat imports and the loss of a 500,000-ton phosphoric acid contract with India. The cost of imports soared 16.6 percent for the first six months, to $2.6 billion, while exports fell 4.6 percent, to $1.5 billion.

abstract: LEAD: LUTSES are loose in Midtown, doing their colorful, frolicsome, cheerful bit to restore the glitter of the Great White Way.

abstract: LEAD: Suedzucker A.G. of West Germany agreed to pay nearly $740 million for a Belgian sugar maker in a deal that puts it in contention to become Europe's biggest sugar producer. abstract: LEAD: Todor I. Zhivkov, Eastern Europe's longest-serving leader, resigned today as Bulgaria's President and Communist Party leader, after 35 years of guiding the country with old-line orthodoxy.

headline: ADVANCE REPORTED ON MIDEAST TALKS
abstract: LEAD: Egypt has agreed, with some conditions, to Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d's plan to prepare for a dialogue between Israeli and Palestinian representatives, the State Department said today.

headline: In Nicaragua, the Election Observers Are Coming!
abstract: LEAD: As national voter registration began today, Nicaraguans got their first look at what will be a huge international effort to preserve peace and supervise free elections in their war-battered country.

headline: East Berlin Fills Void: Road Map of the West
abstract: LEAD: East Germany is about to publish its first road map of West Germany since the 1950's.

abstract: LEAD: I am an American who distributes computer products in Japan. I started with $5,000 in 1972 and now have a company with revenues of $80 million a year. We employ 500 people in Japan, where I live. Most of our revenues are from selling American software products that we import.

headline: C.D.'s and Bank Funds Off
abstract: LEAD: Yields on certificates of deposit and money market accounts at commercial banks and savings institutions were mostly down for the week that ended yesterday.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  THE ECONOMY  Federal regulators and banking experts are concerned that mounting losses from troubled real estate loans could lead to a wave of bank failures, straining the Federal insurance program that protects depositors' funds. The danger, regulators and analysts say, is that when the country enters an economic downturn, as most economists say it eventually must, the losses at commercial banks may be so large that the Government might have to raise insurance fees on the banking industry or rescue some banks with taxpayers' money.

headline: Kohl Aide Meets East Berlin Leaders
abstract: LEAD: East Germany's new leaders held their first talks today with a senior aide to Chancellor Helmut Kohl, while hundreds or thousands of East Germans took to the streets again in Leipzig and several other East German cities to maintain the pressure for change.

headline: A 'New Wave' for the Office
abstract: LEAD: The Hewlett-Packard Company will announce on Tuesday a set of computer programs to allow people to work together electronically even if they use different types of computers and different brands of software.

headline: N.A.M., in Shift, Picks Economist as President
abstract: LEAD: Jerry J. Jasinowski became president of the National Association of Manufacturers this week, setting a sort of precedent. Normally the association recruits an executive of a manufacturing company to be president. Mr. Jasinowski is the first economist named to the group's top job, and he has never even worked in the private sector, except for odd jobs while in college.

headline: Most Bank Yields Decline, Anticipating Drop in Rates
abstract: LEAD: Yields offered for certificates of deposit and money market accounts at commercial banks and savings institutions were mostly down for the week ended yesterday.

headline: New Mexico Paper Sold
abstract: LEAD: The Gannett Company, the Weashington-based media company, said yesterday that it had sold The New Mexican, its Santa Fe, N.M., newspaper, to Robert McKinney, the paper's publisher and editor in chief, and his daughter, Robin McKinney Martin. Mr. McKinney resumed his jobs with the paper in 1987 after a nine-year legal battle with Gannett over his employment contract.

headline: Campeau Faults D.& B.
abstract: LEAD: The Campeau Corporation yesterday sharply criticized Dun & Bradstreet Inc., the credit-rating company, for advising its clients against further merchandise shipments to its stores because of a delay in the proposed sale of its Bloomingdale's department store chain.

headline: U.S. Grants Aquino's Military Quick Sale of Anti-Tank Arms
abstract: LEAD: Fearing that Philippine soldiers loyal to the Government of President Corazon C. Aquino were losing ground again, the Bush Administration granted a Philippine request late Saturday for the quick sale and transfer of hundreds of anti-tank weapons from American bases to Mrs. Aquino's forces, officials said today.

headline: No Forced Layoffs Seen in I.B.M. Cuts
abstract: LEAD: The International Business Machines Corporation, stung by product delays and increasing competition, wants to reduce costs further, but it remains committed to its 40-year-old policy of no forced layoffs, George H. Conrades, an I.B.M. senior vice president, said in an interview.

headline: Fighting in Panama: The United Nations; U.S. Finding Scant Support for Action in Panama
abstract: LEAD: The United States appeared in serious difficulty today as it struggled to win international backing for its assault of Panama and for the newly installed Government of President Guillermo Endara against mounting third world and Soviet criticism of President Bush's action.

headline: Oil Rig Count Dips by 3
abstract: LEAD: The number of working oil and gas rigs in the United States dropped last week by 3, to 1,037, Baker Hughes Inc. reported today. It was the second weekly decline after a string of gains. But the total number of working rigs still reflects 126 more than for the corresponding week a year ago.

headline: Fidelity Is Freeing Its Funds To Be Assertive Investors
abstract: LEAD: In another sign of the increasing power of institutional investors in takeover battles, one of the country's largest mutual fund organizations is taking steps to give it more influence over companies in which it holds stock. Fidelity Investments, whose mutual funds own shares worth $46 billion, has removed investment limitations from 26 of its stock mutual funds in recent months and expects shareholders to approve the removal in its 37 other stock funds by the end of the year.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Airbus Industrie, a consortium of European aircraft manufacturers, said it had received 99 firm orders and 74 options for its proposed short-to-medium range A321 airliner.

headline: Tokyo Journal; For Women and for Socialists, It's Always Uphill
abstract: LEAD: ''Doh-eee! Doh-eee! Doh-eee!'' a crowd of young people chanted the other day as Takako Doi, leader of the Japan Socialist Party, headed toward a microphone in a sleek automobile showroom. At the side of the stage was a poster declaring, ''Doi for Prime Minister.''

headline: Let Manila Use Its Aid For Police, Quayle Says
abstract: LEAD: Vice President Dan Quayle said today that the Bush Administration was considering asking Congress to let the Philippines use some of its American aid to build up its internal security.

headline: Tokyo Stocks Rise In Morning Session
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices in Tokyo continued to climb this morning, despite a decline yesterday in the United States market.

headline: Program Traders Are Defiant
abstract: LEAD: Some money managers who invest the nation's pension fund money vowed yesterday to ignore the New York Stock Exchange's latest attempt to curb computerized program trading.

headline: Seaman Furniture Revamps Finances
abstract: LEAD: The Seaman Furniture Company said it had successfully completed its financial restructuring. The company said its exchange offer to holders of its 15 percent subordinated debentures due in 1999 had been completed, and that the plan had provided more than $40 million in cash reserves and had reduced bank debt from approximately $275 million to $125 million.

headline: Patents; A Protein 'Scaffolding' For Repairing Knees
abstract: LEAD: Kevin Stone, an orthopedic surgeon in San Francisco, has patented a ''scaffolding'' made of protein to help repair the cartilage of people with knee injuries.

headline: Economic Scene; Shifting Spending To Public Works
abstract: LEAD: THE upheaval in Eastern Europe, with its greater openness to the West, means to many Americans that the United States no longer needs a huge military establishment. The Bush Administration, in fact, is beginning to shrink the $300 billion military budget. But if billions of dollars are diverted from military spending over the next decade, how should the money be spent?

headline: Top Polish Communists Prepare for Congress
abstract: LEAD: The Communist Party Central Committee began preparing its program today for a nationwide congress in January that aims to revamp the party and revive its flagging fortunes.

headline: Hooker Corp. Plan Dropped
abstract: LEAD: Lo Yuk-Sui, a Hong Kong real estate owner and developer, said yesterday that he had abandoned his plan to acquire the L. J. Hooker Corporation, the Australian developer with large retailing interests in the United States.

headline: 10 Killed and 100 Are Hurt In Police Clash in Bangladesh
abstract: LEAD: At least 10 people were killed and about 100 wounded in northeastern Bangladesh today when the police opened fire in battles with an angry crowd protecting suspected thieves, officials and witnesses said.

headline: Article 067189 -- No Title
abstract: LEAD: Price Stern Sloan Inc., the book publisher based here, said today that it had lost $8 million in the third quarter and had retained an investment banking firm to help it consider a sale, merger or recapitalization.

headline: Clamor in the East; Moscow Condemns Party Leaders In Lithuania Over a Move to Split
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Communist Party has issued a stinging criticism of party leaders in Lithuania for failing to contain that wayward republic's drive for independence.

headline: Number of Untaxed Companies Is Said to Decline
abstract: LEAD: Many large and profitable companies that once managed to pay little or no Federal income tax have been pushed back onto the tax rolls by the 1986 overhaul of the tax code, Citizens for Tax Justice said today, citing its own survey.

headline: Former Chairman of Haas Guilty in Penny Stock Fraud
abstract: LEAD: The former chairman of a brokerage firm that collapsed after the market crash in October 1987 was convicted yesterday by a Federal jury in Manhattan of participating in a conspiracy to manipulate the prices of three over-the-counter stocks.

headline: 'Brain Drain' in Hong Kong
abstract: LEAD: The exodus of professional people from Hong Kong is so great that economic growth may be only half of projections, a business group warned today. Many emigrants are seeking foreign passports before China takes over the British colony in 1997.

headline: PROFITS SCOREBOARD
abstract: LEAD:            Net      Percent       Income      Change                $      Net Income   Percent        July-Sept.   Change        1989   From '88       W.R. Berkley Corp.   $ 12,100,000    -12.9        Adolph Coors Co.   21,000,000    -2.8        Grumman Corp.   16,900,000    -24.9        Maxus Energy Corp.   (20,000,000)    -       National Steel Corp.

headline: New Competition in Noodle Soup
abstract: LEAD: It happened in automobiles. It happened in computer chips. And once again, after years of ignoring foreign competitors, American companies are waking up to a hot market.

headline: U.S. Fears That Chinese May Again Sell Missiles
abstract: LEAD: A senior Administration official said today that the United States is concerned that China may drop its commitment not to sell medium-range missiles or the technology to make them.

headline: Ashland Pays Iran
abstract: LEAD: Ashland Oil Inc. said it had paid the National Iranian Oil Company $325 million and would charge the payment against results for the year ended Sept. 30. The payment was made under an agreement announced last month that settled all disputes and litigation between the two companies, Ashland said. The Iranian company had been seeking $768 million because an Ashland unit had refused to pay for crude oil in 1979.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Bonn Leader Softens His Plan for German Unity
abstract: LEAD: Taking account of foreign concerns, Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany softened a vital element of his vision of German unity today as representatives of the four wartime occupying powers met here and insisted on ''the importance of stability'' in Eastern Europe.

headline: Impossible Brew
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: Dreaded Virus Said to Cause Little Damage to Computers
abstract: LEAD: A long-feared electronic virus set to cripple personal computers today created high anxiety but caused very little actual damage.

headline: U.S., Saluting Lebanon Vote, Asks an End to Factionalism
abstract: LEAD: The United States welcomed the election of Rene Moawad as President of Lebanon today and urged all the factions to put aside their differences and help him reunify the nation, which has endured 14 years of civil strife.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Havel Makes It Official: He'd Accept Top Billing
abstract: LEAD: Vaclav Havel, the playwright and opposition leader, declared his readiness tonight to become President.

headline: Fighting in Panama: Overview; G.I.'s in Panama Report Gains in Restoring Order
abstract: LEAD: The American military commander here said today that his forces had begun to make significant progress in restoring order in Panama City and the countryside. But there was no indication that the American forces had made any progress toward one of their main goals, the capture of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the dictator who went into hiding when the Americans invaded this country four days ago.

headline: Noriega Linked to Steroid Smuggling, Mexico Says
abstract: LEAD: The Mexican Government's top drug enforcement official has alleged that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the Panamanian leader, is directly involved in the manufacture and smuggling of steroids through Mexico to the United States.

headline: Paging Plan in Europe
abstract: LEAD: The 12 European Community nations agreed today to start a European radio messaging system after 1992 to enable business executives and other users of beepers to page each other across national borders. At present, each country operates its own national paging system and very few systems operate across borders.

headline: EXECUTIVES
abstract: LEAD: * American Cyanamid Co., Wayne, N.J., a chemical manufacturer, appointed John E. Lynch president of the chemicals division of its subsidiary Cyanamid International and Donald J. De Castro president of its Latin American group.

headline: Soviets Said to Double Cambodia Aid
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union has sharply increased its military aid to the Cambodian Government in Phnom Penh this year, roughly doubling deliveries of arms and ammunition over 1988 levels, Asian diplomats and Cambodian rebel leaders say.

headline: Addendum
abstract: LEAD: * The Alfstad Blank Group, an advertising and marketing firm, has opened at 485 Fifth Avenue.

headline: MCI Sues A.T.&T. Over Ads
abstract: LEAD: The MCI Communications Corporation filed suit today in Federal District Court in Washington, accusing the American Telephone and Telegraph Company of false and deceptive advertising in connection with a campaign claiming better quality and service.

headline: Blast at U.S. Offices in Chile
abstract: LEAD: A bomb exploded today in the offices of the American-Chilean culture center in Santiago, causing damage but no injuries, the police said. No group asserted responsibility for the blast at the center, which is partially financed by Washington. But Chile's most active left-wing guerrilla group, the Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic Front, warned last week that it could strike at American interests in Chile to protest the American invasion of Panama.

headline: Ex-Head of MCA Unit Talks to Time Warner
abstract: LEAD: Irving Azoff, the former chairman of the MCA Music Entertainment Group, is expected to join Time Warner Inc. as head of his own record label in a joint venture arrangement, several industry executives said yesterday. which is the umbrella company for the record label, music publishing and amphi theatre operation.

headline: House Panel Delays Hearings on Savings Official
abstract: LEAD: The House Banking Committee said today that it had agreed to postpone for two weeks the testimony of Charles H. Keating Jr., former head of the collapsed Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif.

headline: Dispute in Salvador on Witness in Jesuit Case
abstract: LEAD: President Alfredo Cristiani and officials close to the investigation into the slayings of six Jesuit priests say a woman who linked the army to the killings has failed six F.B.I. lie-detector tests.

headline: Prospects; How to Fix the New Yorker
abstract: LEAD: The 64-year-old New Yorker magazine, acquired by Conde Nast Publications Inc. in 1985 for $200 million, has shown a decline in advertising, although circulation is up. Although it earned $6 million a year at the time of its purchase, many analysts now think the magazine is losing money. Can the New Yorker - famed for its fiction and reportage but now criticized as passe - reverse its fortunes?

headline: Ise Journal; An Ancient Shrine Is Testing a Modern Emperor
abstract: LEAD: Inspired by religious faith, reverence for tradition and simple curiosity, millions of tourists and worshipers go out of their way every year to visit this sacred and historic spot in a densely forested and hilly coastal area of central Japan.

headline: Gandhi Foes Cite Disruptions In First Day of India Voting
abstract: LEAD: As voting began in a national election that will determine the political future of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, opposition politicans asserted today that criminal gangs backed by the governing party were disrupting voting in Mr. Gandhi's own constituency, where independent witnesses also said they had seen policemen stuffing ballot boxes.

headline: FOES OF APARTHEID HOLD UNITY TALKS
abstract: LEAD: More than 4,000 representatives of South Africa's anti-apartheid movement gathered here today to search for a consensus on how to bring down the white minority Government.

headline: Nairobi Journal; Skyscraper's Enemy Draws a Daily Dose of Scorn
abstract: LEAD: On recent mornings, Prof. Wangari Maathai has postponed reading the newspapers until she arrives at the office, where she braces herself over a cup of hot tea for the daily fulminations against her.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Yugoslavia Separatists Urge Break With Serbian Republic
abstract: LEAD: Anti-Communist opposition groups in the Yugoslav republic of Slovenia have joined forces and demanded a break of ties with Serbia.

headline: 63 Killed by Storms in China
abstract: LEAD: A series of three typhoons killed 63 people, and injured 712 in Hainan province in the South China Sea, the official New China News Agency said today. Fifteen people were reported missing, the agency said. The typhoons hit the island from Oct. 2 to 13, according to the agency.

headline: 2 Earthquakes Strike Algeria; 19 Are Dead and 100 Hurt
abstract: LEAD: Two earthquakes about 15 minutes apart struck northern Algeria on Sunday night, killing at least 19 people and injuring about 100, the Interior Ministry reported today. Most of the deaths were in the Tipasa region west of Algiers and in Churchell, on the Mediterranean coast west of the capital.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Y.&R. Pleads Not Guilty
abstract: LEAD: Young & Rubicam pleaded not guilty in Federal District Court in Hartford on Friday to charges that it bribed Jamaican Government officials to obtain the country's tourism advertising account in 1981.

headline: Record on Borrowing Can Help Trump's Bid
abstract: LEAD: Donald J. Trump brings a strong staff and a solid record of repaying bank debts to his $7.1 billion bid for the AMR Corporation, but he suffers from an image as a corporate raider who may not be seriously interested in completing a transaction.

headline: Aquino Asks Immediate Trial Of Army Rebellion Leaders
abstract: LEAD: President Corazon C. Aquino today ordered the immediate trial of leaders of the failed coup this month, branding them traitors who were paid ''30 pieces of silver'' to bring her down. None of the top leaders, however, have been captured.

headline: Sri Lanka Says Army Has Defeated a Tamil Militia in the East
abstract: LEAD: Government troops said today that they had defeated a new Tamil militia accused of killing 38 Muslim police officers in the eastern Ampara district.

headline: 7 Die in Bogota Blast; Police Seek Drug Link
abstract: LEAD: Seven passengers were killed and eight wounded today in a bus bombing here, and the police were trying to determine whether it was linked to the war of cocaine traffickers against the Government.

headline: Upheaval in the East; WORKERS ARE FEW IN POLAND PARTY
abstract: LEAD: Poland's Communist Party is losing touch with the workers, its leaders said today.

headline: Gasoline Prices Decline
abstract: LEAD: Retail gasoline prices fell almost one cent a gallon in the last two weeks, continuing a downward trend, an analyst said. The average price for all grades of gasoline, including taxes, was $1.0816 a gallon, down 0.95 cent from the two-week survey that ended Oct. 20, according to the Lundberg Survey of 12,000 United States service stations.

headline: Europe Lifts Key Rates, But the Dollar Still Rises
abstract: LEAD: In a coordinated effort to weaken the buoyant dollar, the West Germans and other European countries increased key interest rates today, but the dollar closed higher anyway.

headline: Reagan Given Top Award By Japanese
abstract: LEAD: Ronald Reagan was hailed, honored and generally treated like a head of state today while Japanese leaders fondly recalled his Presidency as a time of fewer frictions over trade and other issues.

headline: Clamor in the East; U.S. Officials Believe Gorbachev No Longer Wants Control of East
abstract: LEAD: On the eve of the Malta summit meeting, Administration officials have concluded that the Soviet leader, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, has in essence written off Eastern Europe and no longer feels that direct control there is essential for Soviet security.

headline: CML Group Gets New Jacobs Bid
abstract: LEAD: CML Group Inc. received a revised unsolicited bid from Irwin L. Jacobs, the corporate raider, to acquire CML for $25 a share in cash, or a total of about $167.5 million. CML previously received an unsolicited bid from Mr. Jacobs of $23 a share.

headline: MEXICAN CAPITAL RESTRICTS DRIVING
abstract: LEAD: Responding to public fears that the arrival of winter will push pollution to intolerable levels, the government of the Mexican capital has for the first time imposed restrictions on automobile use and begun putting in place a plan to improve air quality by reducing toxic emissions.

headline: Imbaba Journal; Camels and Men: All Is Changing and Unchanged
abstract: LEAD: Guided by stars and some instinct less defined, Mohammed Abu Jaber has been leading his caravans across the bleached deserts these last 27 years on a route he calls the road of 40 days, whose romance, for his camels at least, ends on the butcher's slab.

headline: Profit Posted At Affiliated
abstract: LEAD: Affiliated Publications Inc., parent company of The Boston Globe, reported last week that it had earned $8.5 million in the third quarter, compared with a loss a year earlier.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Omnicom Earnings Up
abstract: LEAD: The Omnicom Group said its earnings rose by 54 percent, to $5.6 million, in the third quarter of this year, from $3.6 million in the period last year. Its earnings per share jumped by 47 percent, to 22 cents a share, from 15 cents a share in 1988. For the first nine months of 1989, Omnicom's net income grew by 26 percent, to $29.6 million, from $23.5 million.

headline: Market Place; Are Small Stocks Set to Rebound?
abstract: LEAD: IS now the time for small stocks to start outperforming their larger brethren? Some money managers think so, betting both on the much-heralded ''January effect'' - the phenomenon of small stocks rising rapidly around the beginning of a new year - and on the relative cheapness of small stocks.

headline: Boeing and McDonnell Get Taiwan Jet Order
abstract: LEAD: Evergreen Airways, a new international carrier based in Taiwan, has signed deals with two American jet manufacturers to buy as many as 26 jets worth more than $3.2 billion, the manufacturers said today.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Atlas Copco Roctec, Pine Brook, N.J., a mining and engineering company, named Alan Weiner president.

headline: Program Trading Declines
abstract: LEAD: Following a historical pattern, the percentage of program trading on the New York Stock Exchange fell in October from the previous month, the Big Board said yesterday.

headline: Bush Aides Say Gorbachev Sees Economy as Key
abstract: LEAD: In a discussion of Soviet domestic problems with President Bush in Malta, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev called his campaign to end consumer shortages in the Soviet Union ''the ultimate test'' of his leadership, senior Administration officials said today. The Soviet leader reportedly left some American officials with the impression that he was at a loss over how to solve his economic problems.

headline: 3-Part Pricing By USAir
abstract: LEAD: USAir Inc. has offered $245.145 million of pass-through certificates in a three-part pricing.

headline: Existing Home Sales Rise, Spurred by Falling Rates
abstract: LEAD: Sales of existing homes, spurred by a big jump in activity in the South, advanced 3.2 percent in November, climbing at their fastest pace in 11 months, the National Association of Realtors said today.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: Pro Bono
abstract: LEAD: * Calet, Hirsch & Spector has created a newspaper and radio campaign for the first annual New York City coat drive, which is seeking winter coats for homeless and poor people. The campaign, which began on Friday, runs through December 10.

headline: Moscow Gives Disputed Area Back to Azerbaijan
abstract: LEAD: The Supreme Soviet today restored Azerbaijan's control over the territory of Nagorno-Karabakh, the center of a prolonged and violent dispute with neighboring Armenia.

headline: A Craving for the Choicest Glass
abstract: LEAD: FEW people keep them under their pillows or massage them like good-luck charms. But the craving for high-priced objects and goblets of cut glass certainly rivals the craze for the fashionable ''new-age'' crystal rocks, especially during this gift-giving season, when 40 percent of all crystal is sold.

headline: American Medical May Get New Bids
abstract: LEAD: American Medical International Inc., whose directors have accepted a $1.79 billion offer for the hospital concern, said it had been approached by two parties who have indicated that they might make higher bids for the Beverly Hills, Calif., company.

headline: U.S. Created Coup Conditions, Panamanian Asserts at U.N.
abstract: LEAD: The President of the Panamanian Government, who is loyal to General Manuel Antonio Noriega, blamed the United States today for creating conditions that led to the coup attempt in his country.

headline: Lebanese Holds Talks on Unity
abstract: LEAD: Selim al-Hoss, Lebanon's newly appointed Prime Minister, held extensive discussions today in an effort to bring the country's feuding factions together in a government of national reconciliation.

headline: Latin Drug Traffickers Use Canada as New Route
abstract: LEAD: In their seemingly endless search for new ways of smuggling cocaine into the United States, the drug traffickers of South America have created a Canadian connection.

headline: Media General's Profit
abstract: LEAD: Media General Inc. said Friday that its profit had fallen about 63 percent in the latest quarter and attributed the results to weakness in newspaper advertising linage and declines in newsprint sales. Net income dropped to $3.94 million, or 15 cents a share, from $10.78 million, or 38 cents a share, in the year-earlier quarter.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Topps Makes A Move Into Magazines
abstract: LEAD: YOU can't flip it. Nor is it packaged with a brittle stick of stale bubble gum. But the Topps Company is betting that American children will flock to it the way they have to the baseball cards the company has printed since 1951.

headline: Chicago Exchange Alters Rules on Halting Trading
abstract: LEAD: The Chicago Mercantile Exchange announced yesterday that it had tightened the rules for market trading halts, known as circuit breakers, at times when prices drop sharply.

headline: Upheaval in the East: Moscow; Gorbachev Says He Will Confer With Allies on Aid to Rumanians
abstract: LEAD: President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, apparently not referring to military aid, said today that he would confer with Warsaw Pact members on rendering assistance to the Rumanian people in their ''just cause'' of opposing force fighting to restore Nicolae Ceausescu to power.

headline: Jefferies Back On the Stand
abstract: LEAD: Boyd L. Jefferies yesterday recounted before a third jury how he helped manipulate the price of Union Carbide stock three years ago at the request of a senior GAF executive.

headline: 21 Kurds Are Reported Slain In a Reprisal Raid in Turkey
abstract: LEAD: Kurdish guerrillas killed 21 people, 6 of them women and 13 of them children, in a reprisal raid on a pro-Turkish Kurdish village near the Iraqi border, officials said today.

headline: Leading Hard-Line Politician Is Elected to Iran's Parliament
abstract: LEAD: Former Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi of Iran won a seat over the weekend in the country's Parliament, giving him a public platform to advocate the hard-line views held by a wide group of Iranian politicians.

headline: President Quits at Squibb
abstract: LEAD: The Bristol-Myers Squibb Company said yesterday that Jan Leschly, president of the Squibb Corporation, had resigned to pursue opportunities outside the company.

headline: Shanghai Journal; New Challenges for a City of Hope and Past Glory
abstract: LEAD: Below the reconstructed Long Bar, where the foreign taipans, or big bosses, used to sip their pink gins and chat about the women with gowns slit up the leg past the waist, or about rogues of the underworld like Big-Eared Du and Pockmarked Huang, a symbol of the new Shanghai is taking shape.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Hungary to Hold Free Vote On March 25, Leader Says
abstract: LEAD: The Acting President of Hungary, Matyas Szuros, announced today that the country's first competitive elections in 41 years will be held on March 25, the state news agency reported.
