headline: Big Board Chief Backs Increasing S.E.C. Role
abstract: LEAD: John J. Phelan Jr., the chairman of the New York Stock Exchange, gave conditional support today to a proposal to give the Securities and Exchange Commission the power to suspend program trading in the stock and options markets if the market drops by a certain amount.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Ousted Member of Politburo Is Under Custody in Prague
abstract: LEAD: An ousted Czechoslovak Communist Party Politburo member, Miroslav Stepan, has been detained pending an inquiry into his role in security force violence against a democracy protest last month, state television said today.

headline: Fund Shortage For Eurotunnel
abstract: LEAD: Directors of the effort to build a tunnel under the English Channel said today that they would have to raise more money because of a 40 percent increase in the estimated cost of linking Britain and France by rail in 1993.

headline: Lockheed's $300 Million Mistake
abstract: LEAD: The Lockheed Corporation said today that it would subtract $300 million from its pretax fourth-quarter earnings because of a miscalculation it made in bidding for a contract to develop an antisubmarine aircraft for the Navy.

headline: Market Place; Tax Laws Spur Borrowing Boom
abstract: LEAD: IN the era of leverage, its founders do not reside on Wall Street, public perceptions to the contrary. The boom in borrowing can, to a considerable extent, be laid at the doorstep of the Congressional tax law writers.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Bancorp New Jersey Inc., Somerville, N.J., a bank holding company, said it would begin repurchasing 500,000 common shares over five years.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Addenda
abstract: LEAD: * McCann-Erickson Worldwide has established a joint venture with Tara Sinha Associates, an agency based in New Delhi. McCann will hold a 40 percent equity stake in the agency.

headline: GTE Receives $4.5 Million
abstract: LEAD: The GTE Corporation has accepted $4.5 million from Home Shopping Network Inc. as the cash settlement on a $100 million damage award against the retailer, which sells its products on cable television. The two sides announced in

headline: BUSH CLAIMS ROLE IN HOSTAGE RESCUE IN SALVADOR HOTEL
abstract: LEAD: President Bush said today that he had dispatched commandos to San Salvador after rebel forces seized a hotel where American military advisers were staying. He boasted of helping to rescue the hostages in an operation that was launched without seeking approval from the President of El Salvador.

headline: Trade Gap Widest in 10 Months
abstract: LEAD: The nation's trade deficit widened sharply in October to the highest level in 10 months and imports soared to a record level, the Commerce Department reported today.

headline: Kangaroos Sets Merger
abstract: LEAD: Jumping-Jacks Shoes Inc. reached a preliminary agreement last week to merge with Kangaroos U.S.A. Inc., a privately held shoe company. The agreement calls for Jumping-Jacks shareholders to own a 20 percent equity stake in the combined operations, with the rest being owned by Kangaroos shareholders.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Adrien Arpel Inc., a cosmetics business, retained Wertheim Schroder & Co. as a financial adviser for possible sale of the company.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Biocontrol Technology Inc., Indiana, Pa., a biotechnology concern, named T. J. Feola vice president and director of marketing and sales.

headline: Market Place; Minnesota Banks Go Different Ways
abstract: LEAD: FOR decades, First Bank System Inc. and the Norwest Corporation, two large banking companies based in Minneapolis, were so similar that they were often referred to as the Minnesota twins. But these days, the twins are by no means identical. ''They're kind of like Arnold Schwarzenegger and Danny DeVito,'' said Ben Crabtree, a banking analyst at Dain Bosworth Inc.

headline: Emigres Are Given Passage to West
abstract: LEAD: Four weeks to the day after a few thousand East Berliners took to the streets to demand political change, at least a half million demonstrators jammed the heart of the East German capital today for the largest rally so far in what one speaker called a ''revolution from below.''

headline: What to Do With the Cold War Money
abstract: LEAD: THE idea of a ''peace dividend'' first surfaced in 1969. A Cabinet Coordination Committee was set up to report to President Lyndon B. Johnson on what the Federal Government should do with its savings when the War in Vietnam finally ended. The committee proposed that the Federal Government dedicate $39.7 billion a year from its savings - in 1969 dollars - for the upkeep of the infrastructure.

headline: Union Pacific Cuts
abstract: LEAD: The Union Pacific Railroad, a unit of the Union Pacific Corporation, said 190 management employees had accepted retirement or agreed to leave the company. The move represents a 4.4 percent reduction in the railroad's nonunion personnel, it said. The company's management staff now numbers 4,350, down 27 percent in four years.

headline: Clamor in the East; Nadia Comaneci Said to Flee Rumania for Hungary
abstract: LEAD: The Rumanian gymnast Nadia Comaneci, who earned the first perfect score awarded in Olympic gymnastic competition during the 1976 games in Montreal, has fled to Hungary and gone into hiding, Hungarian officials said today.

headline: Clamor in the East; Poles Remove a Hated Statue
abstract: LEAD: To the cheers and song of thousands of onlookers today, workers toppled a statue of Feliks E. Dzerzhinsky, the Polish aristocrat who organized the Soviet secret police after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution.

headline: A Prescription for Troubled I.B.M.
abstract: LEAD: By all accounts, the International Business Machines Corporation is in trouble. Drastic measures are now in order if it is to keep its dominance in computers. Some would even argue that the time has finally arrived for it to drop its stubborn preoccupation with the mainframe, maybe even spin off its minicomputers.

headline: Hong Kong Leader Tries to Tone Down Criticism of Beijing
abstract: LEAD: With Hong Kong's relationship to China growing steadily worse, the colony's governor gave an important policy address today and carefully avoided provoking Beijing.

headline: Convictions Reversed In Ohio Bank Failure
abstract: LEAD: An Ohio appeals court today threw out the convictions of the former owner of the Home State Savings Bank, Marvin L. Warner, and a co-defendant that resulted from the 1985 collapse of the Cincinnati institution.

headline: BUSH SENDING TEAM TO ADVISE POLAND
abstract: LEAD: President Bush announced today that he would send a delegation led by three Cabinet officers to Poland next month to help decide how to spend a package of American aid that is now stalled in Congress.

headline: Chrysler to Halt Subcompact Work
abstract: LEAD: The Chrysler Corporation said it would not build any subcompact cars until the mid-1990's after it stops production of its Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon.

headline: Alaska Spill Jolts Chevron, Too
abstract: LEAD: Public outrage over the 11 million gallons of crude oil that the Exxon Valdez spilled into Alaska's Prince William Sound in March has lashed the industry in many ways. But perhaps no company, Exxon included, has been jolted as badly as the Chevron Corporation.

headline: New Toyota Luxury Car
abstract: LEAD: The Toyota Motor Corporation introduced a high-performance luxury car today that it calls its new flagship automobile. The Celsior features a 4,000-cubic-centimeter, eight-cylinder engine with 260 horsepower.

headline: Rescuing Businesses Is Now a Big Business
abstract: LEAD: Frank J. Zolfo is in a business that booms when others do not. The head of an accounting firm devoted to troubled businesses and their investors, he has thrived on the explosion in demand for services like his own.

headline: Hungarian Says Trade Will Double
abstract: LEAD: Hungary's Minister of Trade predicted today that the United States' recent decision to grant most-favored-nation tariff treatment to Hungary would contribute to a doubling of two-way trade, to $1 billion a year, by the early 1990's.

headline: Outboard Marine Chief Retiring 3 Years Late
abstract: LEAD: The Outboard Marine Corporation's chairman and chief executive, Charles D. Strang, is set to retire, three years late, because he wanted to take the company into the boat business to complement its boat engine business.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; Capitol Records Head Is Focusing on Artists
abstract: LEAD: Hale Milgrim, an executive at Elektra Records since 1984, was named president of Capitol Records yesterday to replace David Berman, who resigned last month because of differences over management.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Saatchi Goes For a Change Of Direction
abstract: LEAD: REVIEWING the most tumultuous period in the 19-year history of the Saatchi & Saatchi Company, a leading European advertising executive said, ''Someone has to reinvent that company.''

headline: Arts Tabloid Prospers By Helping Others Out
abstract: LEAD: Paper, the hip black-and-white tabloid that chronicles New York's downtown arts and culture scene, is building a thriving side business filling other publications' pages. The latest to call was Murdoch Magazines' Mirabella, an erstwhile competitor in covering fashion trends, which retained Paper to write, design and paste up its eight-page ''News'' section for the

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: Boatmen's Bancshares Inc., St. Louis, to TBWA Kerlick Switzer, with a budget of $6 million.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Birtcher Corp., El Monte, Calif., a maker of electromedical and electrosurgical instruments, said it would acquire the Bard/EMS electrosurgery division of C. R. Bard Inc., Murray Hill, N.J., for $11 million.

headline: Upheaval in the East; At Least 13 Are Reported Killed At Protest in Rumania's Capital
abstract: LEAD: Rumanian Government forces clashed with protesters in the streets of Bucharest today as anti-Communist demonstrations spread to the country's capital, Western diplomats there said. The United States Embassy in Bucharest reported that at least 13 protesters had been killed, but diplomats said the demonstrators had not been dispersed.

headline: Soviets, in Bid to Borrow, Set Up Banking Office in New York
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union has quietly established its first banking presence in the United States, a New York office of Moscow's Bank for Foreign Economic Affairs, American and Soviet officials say.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Staples Inc., Newton, Mass., an office-products manufacturer, to Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos/Boston, with a budget of $2 million.

headline: 6 Arrested at Times Building
abstract: LEAD: Six people were arrested last night after blocking the entrance to the New York Times building in Manhattan as a part of a protest against the newspaper's reporting from El Salvador. About 80 people marched and chanted behind police barricades across the street from the paper's offices at 229 West 43d Street.

headline: Namibia Rebel Leader: A Focus of Hope and Fear <
abstract: LEAD: The most famous face in this land belongs to an avuncular Namibian with a white beard and ingratiating smile. The portrait of Sam Nujoma, the leader of the South-West Africa People's Organization, beams from political posters, on the cotton print skirts worn by admiring women and in right-wing graffiti superimposed with a rifle target.

headline: Upheaval in the East; CZECHS NEAR PACT TO PICK PRESIDENT
abstract: LEAD: The Communist Party and the opposition appeared to be moving toward agreement today on a plan to purge Parliament of hard-line Communists to pave the way for the election of a successor to Gustav Husak, the Communist President who stepped down under pressure on Sunday.

headline: UPHEAVAL IN THE EAST: Poland; Opening Way for Aid, Poland Agrees to Economic Change
abstract: LEAD: Poland agreed to far-reaching economic changes in return for as much as $4 billion in Western aid in a letter of intent signed today with the International Monetary Fund.

headline: Osaka Journal; Impatient City's Mission: Steal Tokyo's Thunder
abstract: LEAD: As if this proud commercial city didn't have enough problems, word got out recently that Godzilla would be rampaging through town.

headline: Amid New Famine Worry, Ethiopia Talks Advance
abstract: LEAD: The Ethiopian Government and one of the rebel groups opposing it said today that they had agreed on procedures for substantive peace talks to begin early next year.

headline: CONGRESS TO LIMIT BUSH ON SPY FUNDS
abstract: LEAD: Defying a veto threat from President Bush, House and Senate negotiators agreed today on legislation that would sharply restrict the President's power to solicit funds from foreign countries to carry out intelligence operations and other activities overseas.

headline: Pretoria Official Meets Guerrillas In Namibia for 'Friendly' Talks
abstract: LEAD: South Africa's Foreign Minister held what he called friendly and constructive talks today with the South-West Africa People's Organization, the group that has fought South African rule of the territory for 23 years.

headline: Call for Dialogue Raises Doubts in East Germany
abstract: LEAD: Diplomats and opposition leaders in East Germany reacted with caution and some skepticism today to a statement by the Politburo calling for discussion of national problems while making it clear that Communism was not negotiable.

headline: FINANCE/NEW ISSUES;
abstract: LEAD: The Matagorda County Navigation District One of Texas is offering $70.3 million in 30-year collateralized pollution-control revenue bonds for a Houston Lighting and Power Company project through underwriters led by Goldman, Sachs & Company.

headline: Merieux Bid Gains
abstract: LEAD: Institut Merieux S.A. agreed to spend about $42.5 million to pay for biotechnology research in Canada, clearing an obstacle in its friendly bid of $942 million (Canadian) for the vaccine maker Connaught Biosciences Inc. The agreement was reached with Connaught's founder, the University of Toronto, which had been opposing the bid on the ground that a foreign takeover would mean a loss of research spending and jobs in Canada.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; Chief of Consolidated To Retire Next Month
abstract: LEAD: The Consolidated Stores Corporation, the nation's largest retailer of close-out merchandise, said yesterday that James M. Guinan, its chairman and chief executive for the last 16 months, will retire by the end of January.

headline: The U.N. Today

headline: End for 'Junk Bond' Takeovers?
abstract: LEAD: Institutional investors behaved yesterday as if the takeover craze had ended. Mindful of recent turmoil in the ''junk bond'' market, they grew concerned that corporate acquisitions, which have done much to drive up stock prices in recent years, would grind to a halt because of a lack of credit.

headline: Unusual Cold Spell Sends Energy Prices Up Sharply
abstract: LEAD: Energy prices exploded yesterday, as unseasonably cold weather upset refinery and distribution programs for heating oil. The unusually cold weather so early in the heating season has found some refiners and fuel oil distributors in the Northeast with relatively low stocks of heating oil.

abstract: LEAD: At the Immanuel Kirchstrasse Police precinct in East Berlin's Prenzlauer Berg district, thousands of East Germans lined up today to receive visas allowing them to travel freely to the West.

abstract: LEAD: As a child, David Kirschner says, he was a dreamer.

headline: Police Scatter Algiers Protest
abstract: LEAD: The police fired tear gas on Sunday to disperse hundreds of people protesting poor road conditions in the hills above the capital. No arrests or injuries were reported. The protesters, mostly Muslim fundamentalists, gathered to protest the city's failure to make repairs.

headline: After 25 Years, Pretoria Frees Sisulu
abstract: LEAD: Walter Sisulu, South Africa's second leading jailed black nationalist after Nelson Mandela, was returned to his home today by the police after 25 years in prison.

headline: Magazines Plot Invasion Of Salons
abstract: LEAD: EVER vigilant in the search for new magazine markets to conquer, two publishers have opened a battle for supremacy in another venue uncrowded by specialty journals: beauty parlors.

headline: Comptroller Asserts Banks Face Growing Realty Woes
abstract: LEAD: Robert L. Clarke, the Comptroller of the Currency, said yesterday that bank problems with bad real estate loans were growing but were not yet serious enough to cause losses of the magnitude that led to the collapse of most large Texas banks a few years ago.

headline: HUNGARY LEGALIZES OPPOSITION GROUPS
abstract: LEAD: The Hungarian Parliament formally legalized opposition political parties today, voting overwhelmingly to end more than four decades of one-party rule.

headline: Market Place; A Crucial Vote At Cypress Fund
abstract: LEAD: ONE of the longest-running disputes in the world of closed-end funds comes to a conclusion today as Cypress Fund shareholders vote on whether to throw out management.

headline: EXECUTIVES

headline: Uncovered Short Sales Fall 4.3% on the Big Board
abstract: LEAD: The New York Stock Exchange reported yesterday that short interest had dropped 4.3 percent in the four-week period that ended Oct. 13. Short interest is the number of shares sold short by investors and not yet covered.

headline: India's Homespun Chic (Nothing Imported)
abstract: LEAD: It was probably inevitable that in the high-tech era that has now gone down in history as ''Rajiv's India,'' someone would find a way to put a gloss on ethnicity.

headline: Sharp Rise of Private Guard Jobs
abstract: LEAD: Walk into a store, and a security guard looks you over. Try to enter the lobby of an apartment building and a doorman blocks the way. Arrive for an appointment at a company office and a receptionist politely but firmly checks to see if the appointment really exists.

headline: I.B.M. Vice President Heads Rolm Venture
abstract: LEAD: The Rolm Company officially began operations yesterday as a joint venture of the International Business Machines Corporation and Siemens A.G. of West Germany, with H. Mitchell Watson Jr. at the helm.

headline: Deal to Buy MGM/UA Collapses
abstract: LEAD: An Australian entertainment company's deal to acquire the MGM/UA Communications Company collapsed today amid recriminations and legal action, opening the possibility that Rupert Murdoch might make another bid for the film and television studio.

headline: BREAKS ARE ADDED IN TAX-CUT PLANS
abstract: LEAD: Supporters of a lower tax on capital gains are waging a bidding war in the Senate, offering ever more generous tax breaks in an effort to find the 60 votes they need to overcome parliamentary obstacles.

headline: Kohl Recalls Auschwitz And Agrees to Aid Poles
abstract: LEAD: Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany ended his visit to Poland today with a wreath-laying ceremony for the victims at Auschwitz and the signing of an agreement to provide Poland with $2.2 billion in economic assistance.

headline: All 107 Aboard Killed as Colombian Jet Explodes
abstract: LEAD: A Colombian passenger jet crashed on the outskirts of Bogota shortly after takeoff today, and all 107 people aboard were killed. A caller to a radio station asserted that drug traffickers had bombed the plane.

headline: 3 Drug Makers Post Mixed Results
abstract: LEAD: Three large drug companies yesterday reported mixed results in third-quarter earnings, but analysts said the results at each company were in line with expectations.

headline: Brazil Confirms Collor Won And His Opponent Concedes
abstract: LEAD: The Government confirmed today that Fernando Collor de Mello, an advocate of a free-market economy, won the first free presidential election in Brazil in 29 years.

headline: 9.1% Stake Held In Enzo Biochem
abstract: LEAD: An investment group led by J. Morton Davis, the chairman and sole shareholder of the New York brokerage firm D. H. Blair & Company, said it holds a 9.1 percent stake in Enzo Biochem Inc. In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Mr. Davis said the group might seek to gain control of Enzo Biochem but that it had no immediate plans to do so.

headline: Retailers Are Wary Of Season
abstract: LEAD: Perhaps more than in any year since 1974, when a severe recession started before Thanksgiving, the success of the Christmas shopping season that begins tomorrow is uncertain. But for bargain-hunting shoppers, opportunities may abound.

headline: New Growth in a Captive Market
abstract: LEAD: WITH prison systems strained by overcrowding and law-enforcement officials burdened by record numbers of drug-related arrests, states and municipalities throughout the United States are using electronic monitoring devices to turn an offender's home into a prison cell.

headline: A New Industry Springs Up: Europe 1992
abstract: LEAD: While many American businesses are still trying to figure out how to take advantage of the 12-nation European Community's move to a single market economy in 1992, others are already profiting from it.

headline: Texaco Star Rises Again
abstract: LEAD: DURING the past five years, Texaco Inc. has earned some dubious distinctions. It became the victim of the largest damage award in history when a court ordered it to pay the Pennzoil Company $11 billion for illegally elbowing it aside to acquire the Getty Oil Company in 1984. It also became the largest company to file for protection from creditors under the bankruptcy law and the biggest target ever stalked by Carl I.

headline: Japan Will Help Poland and Hungary
abstract: LEAD: Responding to appeals from the Bush Administration and European nations, Japan has announced that it would provide $150 million in loans to Poland as an initial step to help both Poland and eventually Hungary deal with their financial crises and break loose from the Soviet bloc.

headline: Tokyo Drops Issue of Lost U.S. Bomb
abstract: LEAD: Japan has agreed to drop its demand for further information about the circumstances in which a hydrogen bomb fell overboard from an American aircraft carrier 24 years ago off the coast of Okinawa, Japanese and American officials said today.

headline: U.S. Donor Provides Israeli Immigrant Fund
abstract: LEAD: Natan Sharansky, the former Soviet Jewish dissident now living in Israel, announced today that a private $20 million fund to provide housing for Soviet Jewish immigrants has been created with a single donation from an American businessman.

headline: Sri Lanka Reports Death of Top Sinhalese Militant
abstract: LEAD: The last senior leader of a Sinhalese extremist group has been captured and killed, and the dominant Tamil militants have ambushed and killed members of a rival Tamil organization, Sri Lankan officials said today.

headline: Mack Chairman Resigns
abstract: LEAD: John B. Curcio resigned this week as chairman of Mack Trucks Inc., effective when a successor is named, the company said. Mr. Curcio, 56 years old, had relinquished the post of president to Ralph Reins in June, when expectations of a loss in the second quarter were announced. He surrendered the chief executive's job to Mr.

headline: Warsaw Pact Alliance to Meet
abstract: LEAD: The Warsaw Pact military alliance will meet in Moscow after the Soviet-American summit meeting this weekend, a Polish Government spokesman said today. Solidarity officials said Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Soviet President, would brief Warsaw Pact members on his talks with President Bush.

headline: After 16 Years, Chief Gives Up Hardee's Job
abstract: LEAD: At Hardee's Food Systems Inc., a chief executive with one of the longest tenures in the fast-food industry is stepping down.

headline: American Express to Sell Geneva Bank for $1 Billion
abstract: LEAD: The American Express Company has reached an agreement to sell its Geneva-based private banking subsidiary to another Swiss banking institution for about $1 billion, American Express said yesterday.

headline: CAR MAKERS AND CREDIT UNIONS ENCOURAGE DEALER HONESTY
abstract: LEAD: Car dealers once were ranked alongside fast-talking politicians and snake-oil salesmen. But some are trying to create a kinder, gentler image.

headline: After 30 Years, Japan Patents Chips
abstract: LEAD: Japan granted a patent that Texas Instruments Inc. had been seeking since 1960. The patent covers the basic semiconductor chip, which the company's researchers invented in 1958. The Tokyo decision requires all Japanese chip makers to pay royalties to Texas Instruments. Japanese chip makers have about 90 percent of the Japanese chip market and 80 percent of the United States market.

headline: Flaw in Chip Made by Intel Is Discovered
abstract: LEAD: The Intel Corporation said yesterday that design flaws had been discovered in its top-of-the-line microprocessor chip but that the errors would be corrected quickly and would not hurt its ability to ship ''tens of thousands'' of the chip before the end of the year.

headline: Changes in East Call for a U.S. Balancing Act
abstract: LEAD: A senior policy maker was explaining the other day that the Bush Administration had two sets of policies for Eastern Europe - one for that night's network news and one for the year 2010. But the real challenge for Washington, he said, will be developing approaches to Europe not for tonight and not for the next century, but for next year, 1992 and 1995.

headline: INVESTING; Cashing In on a Construction Boom
abstract: LEAD: After the San Francisco earthquake, many engineering and construction stocks jumped. Speculators quickly concluded that the disaster would provide a big new source of profits. Analysts were less impressed. Most of the cleanup work is likely to go to small private companies, they say.

headline: Lithuanians Backing Communist Party Split
abstract: LEAD: Thousands of Lithuanians have rallied behind their Communist Party's decision to split with Moscow, officials in the rebellious Baltic republic said today.

headline: Woman Dies in Bus Accident
abstract: LEAD: A tourist bus on a foggy Golan Heights highway swerved, apparently to avoid a car, and overturned into a ravine today, killing a West German woman and injuring the bus driver, a guide and 48 West German passengers, the police said. Druse villagers, Jewish settlers, military doctors and emergency medical service workers from the nearby town of Qiryat Shemona helped in the rescue operations.

headline: Schroder Unit Sells Stakes to 3
abstract: LEAD: Wertheim Schroder Holdings Inc., the New York-based investment bank that specializes in international mergers, said yesterday that it had sold 15 percent of the company to three financial institutions for about $50 million.

abstract: LEAD: The board of the McDonald's Corporation yesterday promoted its president and chief executive, Michael R. Quinlan, 45 years old, to chairman and chief executive, effective March 31.

The announcement came two weeks after a top executive said the company expected worldwide sales growth of more than 20 percent. Apple's stock dropped $3.25 a share today, to $36, in over-the-counter trading on volume of more than 9.1 million shares.

abstract: LEAD: A commodities trading firm agreed to pay a $500,000 fine and withdraw from membership in the Chicago Mercantile Exchange to settle charges of improper record-keeping and violating margin requirements, exchange officials said today.

abstract: LEAD: The European Community today rebuffed Turkey's application to join, saying it wanted to wait until 1993 before beginning negotiations about membership for the nation.

abstract: LEAD: In a big victory for the American Telephone and Telegraph Company, the Federal Communications Commission ruled yesterday that the company could continue to offer customized networks for large business customers.

abstract: LEAD: An oasis spring soaks the desert green at Wadi Natrun, and a cloister bell beckons the faithful to prayer and pilgrims to rest and succor.

headline: Your Money; Many Advised To Review Wills

abstract: LEAD: The MCI Communications Corporation and the GTE Corporation reported sharply higher third-quarter earnings yesterday. Another telephone company, the Southwestern Bell Corporation, said its profits had fallen, mainly because of one-time factors.

The clash, north of Merj 'Uyun, came hours after the army said Israeli-backed Lebanese militiamen shot and killed two other guerrillas in the zone. Officials were unable to say if the victims were Palestinian or Lebanese guerrillas.

abstract: LEAD: Congressional negotiations on a budget deal that would provide a separate vote on cutting the capital gains tax continued today, marked by a round of partisan finger-pointing.

abstract: LEAD: Saudi Arabia proposed today that Lebanon's Parliament meet in Beirut in two weeks to elect a new President and start putting into effect political changes intended to end 14 years of civil war.

abstract: LEAD: Donald J. Trump yesterday withdrew his $120-a-share offer for the AMR Corporation, the parent of American Airlines, and said he would review his options.

The denial was issued after Radio D.D.R. reported that that such attacks had taken place. A spokesman said that groups showed signs of wanting to attack the depots, perhaps to obtain weapons, but that they did not carry out the attacks.

abstract: LEAD: WHILE investors, bankers and lawyers on Wall Street might welcome a bruising fight between the Chevron Corporation, with a potential takeover value exceeding $30 billion, and the Pennzoil Corporation, such a battle supreme does not seem likely for now.

abstract: LEAD: It was George Bush's first visit to Poland, and when talk over dinner turned to Solidarity, the Polish leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, picked at his food and said the banned union no longer existed. It was just a bunch of people that John Davis was always having to dinner.

headline: Article 017289 -- No Title

In the 1988 third quarter the computer company had earned $151 million, or 77 cents a share.

headline: Deng Hints at Keeping a Large Role in China
abstract: LEAD: Deng Xiaoping, China's senior leader, suggested today that he might continue to play a significant role in Chinese affairs, despite his resignation from his last formal post in the Communist Party leadership.

abstract: LEAD: East Germany's largest opposition group is filing charges against the former Communist leader, Egon Krenz, over destruction of sensitive security police papers, the official press agency, A.D.N., said today.

abstract: LEAD: The Zemex Corporation, a producer of industrial minerals, metal powders and tin, said yesterday that Gerard E. Wood had been named its new president and chief executive.

headline: Mother Teresa Out of Hospital

The agency quoted hospital officials as saying Mother Teresa, the 79-year-old Nobel Peace Prize winner, had been advised to rest for at least two weeks.

headline: PRAGUE PREMIER SEES TOP FOES, SHARES PLATFORM WITH DUBCEK; PARTY CALLS SPECIAL CONGRESS
abstract: LEAD: The caretaker Prime Minister in Czechoslovakia's Communist Government met today for the first time with leaders of the foremost opposition grouping and then joined Alexander Dubcek at another rally of 500,000 cheering people, who continued to demand democratic changes.

abstract: LEAD: Allegheny International Inc., which had indicated it would not seriously consider a $683.8 million takeover offer from Japonica Partners L.P., has decided to let the New York investment group review its records. ''We're pleased that the board is now apparently cooperating, and we are looking forward to completing a transaction that is in the best interests of creditors and shareholders,'' said Fredric Spar, a Japonica spokesman.

headline: Cahners Magazine Head In Shift to Trade Shows
abstract: LEAD: Neil Perlman is switching from publishing magazines to running trade shows, and he sees similarities between the endeavors. Mr. Perlman, now with Cahners Publishing, has been named the president of Cahners Exposition Group, which produces large trade shows.

headline: Turkish President Sworn In And Appoints a New Premier
abstract: LEAD: Turgut Ozal, Prime Minister for the last six years, was sworn in as President today in a Parliament ceremony boycotted by opposition parties. He named Yildirim Akbulut, Speaker of Parliament, as Prime Minister.

abstract: LEAD: Unilever, the diversified British-Dutch consumer products company, said today that it had acquired Compania Productora Nacional de Aceitas S.A. of Chile for an undisclosed sum. The company, which employs 350 people, manufactures margarine and edible fats and oils, and had 1988 sales of $28 million.

abstract: LEAD: The Honda Motor Company of Japan can supply Israel with adequate spare parts for the American-built cars that the company's United States subsidiary plans to sell in Israel, a spokesman said today.

headline: Ashton-Tate Reports Loss
abstract: LEAD: The Ashton-Tate Company, as expected, reported a loss today, as revenues in its third quarter declined from a year ago.

headline: PAKISTAN WORKING TO FREE P.O.W.'s
abstract: LEAD: Pakistani officials trying to bring an end to the Afghan civil war have apparently succeeded in saving at least four Soviet prisoners of war whose hopes for survival were considered bleak.

headline: Eastern Air Said to Be Near Deal
abstract: LEAD: In an agreement that is close to being signed, American Airlines would buy the Latin American routes of Eastern Airlines for almost $350 million and pay Continental Airlines about $100 million to settle a lawsuit over American's computerized airline reservations system, a person close to the negotiations said yesterday.

abstract: LEAD: Japan's decision to award a lucrative computer chip patent to Texas Instruments Inc. is probably not a sign that the Japanese patent system will be streamlined, patent and trade specialists say. American manufacturers have long contended that Japan's system is rigged against them.

abstract: LEAD: The Boeing Company, one of the nation's largest military contractors, has agreed to plead guilty to two felony charges of illegally obtaining Pentagon planning documents, Government officials said today.

headline: Diplomats at Japan's Embassy Worry About Anti-Tokyo Sentiment in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: The Japanese Embassy here is modest, quiet and plain. The unadorned three-story building on a tree-lined street does not look like the outpost of an economic superpower.

headline: Vote on Gains Tax Fails in Senate
abstract: LEAD: In a long-awaited test vote on cutting the capital gains tax, Senate Republicans today mustered 51 supporters for reducing the tax rate. That is nine short of the 60 needed to overcome the parliamentary hurdles that have blocked the Administration from winning the reduction this year.

Aristech said its board would make a response ''at the appropriate time.

headline: PRICES OF TREASURY ISSUES UNCHANGED

abstract: LEAD: The New York Times Company yesterday reported third-quarter earnings of $210.8 million, or $2.68 a share, compared with $26.7 million, or 33 cents a share, in the comparable period last year. Revenues came to $415.3 million, up 6.4 percent from $390.5 million a year ago.

headline: Business and Health; Two Companies Cut Medical Costs
abstract: LEAD: TWO large employers that were among the earliest to make vigorous attempts to control their medical costs are reporting some successes. They are among a growing number of large companies that are keeping their medical inflation well below the 20 percent or more that is being absorbed by many other businesses.

headline: Gorbachev Says It's Not Time For Soviet Private Property
abstract: LEAD: President Mikhail S. Gorbachev says the Soviet Union is not ready for private property or competing political parties, but is leaving the door open for both in the future.

headline: Iran Releases 50 Iraqi War Prisoners to Red Cross
abstract: LEAD: Iran released 50 ailing or disabled Iraqi prisoners of war to Red Cross representatives today as a gesture of good will, the official Teheran radio reported.

headline: Dow Off 16.18, to 2,610.25, After Early Gains
abstract: LEAD: Stocks fell across a broad front yesterday on moderately higher volume.

headline: Treasuries Steady; Trading Slow
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury securities were little changed yesterday in slow trading, despite a report that showed housing starts were at their lowest level in more than five years.

headline: Clamor in Europe; Leipzig: Where Indignation Has Transformed Politics
abstract: LEAD: At dinner the restless 13-year-old girl volunteered what was troubling her. ''I have such anger!'' she blurted out, talking loudly and very fast. ''I am so mad at my teachers, all of them ignorant party hacks; at the police, who are still training their video cameras at us when we march in demonstrations.

headline: Growth Still Modest, Fed Report Says
abstract: LEAD: The nation's economic growth continued to vary from slow to moderate early this fall, the Federal Reserve said today in its latest economic survey, but it did not mention any inflationary problems.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Bowater Industries, London, which acquired the Norton Opax P.L.C. printing group in September, sold Norton's 3 percent stake in De La Rue Co., a security printer. The price was $:13 million and no buyer was disclosed.

headline: Mubarak Repeats Offer to Meet With Shamir
abstract: LEAD: The Egyptian President, Hosni Mubarak, made a rare telephone call to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Friday night and repeated a conditional offer to meet with the Israeli leader, an official said today.

headline: Protest Ends on Indian Ocean Isle
abstract: LEAD: Soldiers used tear gas and clubs today to disperse 1,000 high school students protesting a coup in which the island nation's president was killed, witnesses said.

headline: In Czech Border Town, Another Day of Rush Hour
abstract: LEAD: The rush of East Germans fleeing through Czechoslovakia to West Germany showed little sign of abating today.

headline: Small Airline Merger Offer
abstract: LEAD: StatesWest Airlines Inc., a small regional carrier based in Phoenix, said today that it had sent a letter to Mesa Airlines Inc. of Farmington, N.M., proposing that the two airlines meet within 10 days to discuss a merger.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; TBWA Advertising Is Chosen by Steuben
abstract: LEAD: Steuben, whose advertising account has been up for grabs since Doyle Graf Raj dissolved earlier this year, has chosen TBWA Advertising after a six-month search.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  INTERNATIONAL  Military contractors are turning abroad for parts to build weapons systems, as the Pentagon puts pressure on companies to reduce costs and as foreign suppliers become more adept. The trend is raising fears on dependence, jobs and profits.  [ Page A1. ] A plan to phase out many American farm programs if other countries agree to similar cutbacks will be put forward this week by the Bush Administration.

headline: Iran Agrees to Allow Visit by U.N. Rights Inspector
abstract: LEAD: For the first time since the revolution that overthrew the Shah, the Iranian Government has agreed in writing to allow a United Nations inspector to enter the country to investigate human rights abuses, diplomats say.

headline: Chile Will Vote Freely This Week, Thanks in Part to Allende's Followers
abstract: LEAD: Jorge Arrate has about him the air of an aging, if well-trimmed, hippie. It comes partly from his graying beard and choice of a home in a slightly Bohemian art district, but mostly from his words.

headline: British Water Share Price Cut
abstract: LEAD: In an attempt to attract investors, the Government has reduced the price for shares in Britain's water industry.

headline: PRAGUE PARTY LEADERS RESIGN; NEW CHIEF, 48, SURPRISE CHOICE; 350,000 AT RALLY CHEER DUBCEK
abstract: LEAD: Yielding to mass protests throughout Czechoslovakia, the Communist Party's leadership resigned on Friday, and the beleaguered Central Committee chose a younger, lesser-known Politburo member to replace General Secretary Milos Jakes.

headline: U.S. Thinks Twice About Armenian Measure
abstract: LEAD: Opposition is mounting in Congress and in the Bush Administration to a resolution before the Senate to declare a national day of remembrance for the widespread killings of Armenians by Ottoman Turks during World War I. President Bush increased Administration efforts to defeat the resolution last week by writing letters to Senator Bob Dole, the Republican minority leader and chief sponsor of the measure, and other congressional leaders.

headline: Change in Leadership Is Expected in Turkey
abstract: LEAD: Turkey seemed headed for new Government leadership today when Prime Minister Turgut Ozal announced that he would run for President in an election that starts in Parliament this week.

headline: Dow Soars 41.38, to 2,747.65; Interest Rate Hopes a Factor
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices registered their biggest gain in weeks yesterday, buoyed by heavy foreign and institutional buying.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Ecology As Applied To the Media
abstract: LEAD: IN a pastoral Catskills setting more appropriate for musings on nature and ecology, a claque of cigarette-smoking urban intellectuals gathered recently to ruminate on the state of the world's media ecology.

headline: U.S. Textile Imports Up
abstract: LEAD: United States textile imports rose by 13 percent and their value climbed to more than $32 billion in 1989, the American Textile Manufacturers Institute said today.

headline: Logistics: A Trendy Management Tool
abstract: LEAD: EARLY last year, the distribution system at Alpo Petfoods Inc. was a major disappointment for top management. The company's 14 warehouses were located near its customers, but service nevertheless was wanting. In fact, in a survey of its 400 major customers, the company, based in Allentown, Pa., was rated below several of its rivals in service.

headline: MANY CLERICS BACK LEFTIST IN BRAZIL
abstract: LEAD: ''Are you rich, well off?'' Antonio Mamede, a Roman Catholic priest, asks straw-hatted farm workers in the fields of Maranhao State in northeast Brazil. ''Well, if you are, then vote for Fernando Collor de Mello because he is the candidate of the rich.''

headline: Sugar Quota Is Increased
abstract: LEAD: The United States Agriculture Department increased the nation's sugar quota today by 13.5 percent, the second time in three months that the Government has increased imports to combat tight supplies and high domestic prices.

headline: Campbell Group Files Plan to Sell
abstract: LEAD: Since April, when John T. Dorrance Jr., the head of the family that owns almost 59 percent of the Campbell Soup Company, died, Wall Street has buzzed with speculation that the Dorrances would sell the company. For eight months, the family issued unanimous denials.

headline: U.S. Corn Sale to Soviets
abstract: LEAD: Private exporting companies have sold an additional 103,632 metric tons of United States corn to the Soviet Union for delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday. The sales were made by unidentified private exporting companies, which are required to report large sales to the department.

headline: RJR Nabisco Planning $1.25 Billion Note Sale
abstract: LEAD: The RJR Nabisco Holding Corporation said yesterday that it had completed the first phase of its plan to reduce its $25 billion debt and would embark on the next stage - refinancing its remaining debt - by seeking Government clearance to sell $1.25 billion in new senior notes.

headline: Treasuries Gain on 'Junk' Sales
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury securities moved higher yesterday, pushed by renewed selling in the high-yield ''junk bond'' market and a larger-than-expected increase in weekly unemployment claims.

headline: MCA Net Down 6.6%
abstract: LEAD: MCA Inc. reported today that its third-quarter earnings declined 6.6 percent, to $50.8 million, or 69 cents a share, from $54.3 million, or 74 cents a share, a year earlier. The company's revenues increased 12.2 percent, to $918.4 million, from $806.7 million in the period last year. Despite record revenues, generated partly from box office hits like ''Parenthood'' and ''Uncle Buck,'' earnings dipped because of increased interest expenses caused by higher interest rates and higher average borrowings compared with 1988.

headline: 'Junk Bonds' Surge in Moderate Trading
abstract: LEAD: Prices of ''junk bonds'' climbed sharply yesterday in moderate trading by dealers and investors, traders said.

headline: May to Buy Back 14 Million Shares
abstract: LEAD: The May Department Stores Company said it had agreed to purchase more than 14 million shares of its common stock from May Centers Associates for $663 million. A May spokesman said the agreement also calls for the purchase by May Centers and leaseback to May of department store properties owned by May and valued at $585 million.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Clayton & Dublier, an investment firm, said its APS Acquisition unit had completed the purchase of A.P.S. Inc., Houston, which distributes auto parts, from Wickes Cos., Santa Monica, Calif. The price was $200 million.

headline: O.E.C.D. Is Optimistic On American Economy
abstract: LEAD: The United States can avoid both a recession and excessive inflation next year, so long as the Federal Reserve keeps an even grip on credit, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development says in a report to be released on Monday.

headline: Microsoft Expects Higher Revenues
abstract: LEAD: The Microsoft Corporation said it expects to report revenues of about $235 million for the quarter ended Sept. 30, an increase of about 34 percent above the $176 million it reported for the comparable period a year ago. The company said it would release complete earnings information on Oct. 17. Frank Gaudette,

headline: New I.B.M. Disk Drive Is Ready
abstract: LEAD: The International Business Machines Corporation said yesterday that it would begin shipping its newest disk drive storage system before most analysts' expectations, improving the company's financial prospects for 1990.

headline: Qintex Seeks Receivership
abstract: LEAD: Qintex Australia Ltd., the troubled media and resort empire of Christopher C. Skase, went into receivership today to stop a sale to pay $1.6 billion in debts.

headline: Accounting Rule Dispute
abstract: LEAD: Upset by a decision that would limit the jurisdiction of the Governmental Accounting Standards Board, nine organizations representing state and local government officials said yesterday that they would withdraw their financial support from the board and start their own rule-making body.

headline: Demonstrators Support Ukrainian Church
abstract: LEAD: Tens of thousands of Ukrainians demonstrated in three cities in the vast southern republic today to demand the legalization of the Ukrainian Catholic Church, banned since the rule of Stalin, campaigners for religious rights reported.

headline: Prospects for Pact on Long-Range Arms Next Year Called Difficult
abstract: LEAD: A senior Administration official suggested today that it was unlikely that Washington and Moscow could conclude a strategic arms treaty next year.

headline: Centrust Payouts
abstract: LEAD: Centrust Bank of Miami said yesterday that it had been ordered to stop paying dividends on its preferred stock because of financial problems including losses in its holdings of ''junk bonds.'' The order to stop paying dividends came from Federal regulators at the Office of Thrift Supervision. Federal and state regulators are considering a proposal by Centrust to sell 63 of its branches for $150 million to the Great Western Financial Corporation of Beverly Hills, Calif.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Czechoslovak Communists Replace Chairman of Party
abstract: LEAD: Czechoslovakia's Communists ousted the party leader today and elected as party chairman a former Prime Minister who has emerged as one of the more conciliatory leaders in the recent weeks of dramatic upheaval.

headline: Ortega's Foray: A Stunning Misstep
abstract: LEAD: When President Daniel Ortega Saavedra set out Friday morning for a presidential summit meeting in Costa Rica, he carried with him a carefully constructed political bombshell: a decision to renew combat operations against American-backed rebels.

headline: South Africa Decides to Open All Beaches to Blacks
abstract: LEAD: President F. W. de Klerk ordered today that South Africa's beaches be opened to all races. He said that some other public places, including libraries and parks, would be desegregated soon.

headline: Buyers Sought for Historic Houses
abstract: LEAD: Two vacant, deteriorating houses of historic significance in Collis P. Huntington State Park in Redding, Conn., are facing demolition because the state sees no reason to preserve them, but they may yet get a reprieve.

headline: India Raises The Estimate Of Its Debt
abstract: LEAD: India's new Finance Minister has said the country's external debt is about $60.6 billion, or nearly twice the figure given by the previous Government.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Bank of America, San Francisco, named Robert A. Johnson senior vice president.

headline: IN QUOTES
abstract: LEAD: ''The United States enjoyed an unprecedented building boom during the 1980's, with overbuilding and an oversupply of office space, shopping centers, hotels - just about everything, all over the country. Texas was not an anomaly, it was a precursor.'' - David Shulman, director of real estate research, Salomon Brothers Inc.

headline: Moldavian Party Leader Is Ousted After Clashes
abstract: LEAD: The Communist Party leader in the Moldavian Soviet Republic, Semyon K. Grossu, was dismissed today after clashes over the weekend between police and nationalist demonstrators in which 200 people were wounded.

headline: NCR Authorizes Stock Repurchase
abstract: LEAD: The board of the NCR Corporation authorized the repurchase of up to 15 million shares, or about 21 percent, of NCR's common stock in the next two years as part of the company's continuing stock repurchase program. NCR's shares were unchanged today on the New York Stock Exchange, closing at $58.875.

headline: Prague Regains a Wayward Balladeer
abstract: LEAD: One of Czechoslovakia's best-known balladeers looked out at the people packed into an auditorium here tonight, nodded his head and smiled.

headline: Data General Founder Gives Up Some Duties
abstract: LEAD: The founder of the Data General Corporation, Edson D. deCastro, yesterday relinquished the titles of president and chief executive to Ronald L. Skates, who joined the computer maker in 1986 as a senior vice president.

headline: Pharmacy-Food Effort With Volvo
abstract: LEAD: Volvo A.B., the Swedish auto maker, announced today that it would join the Government as equal partner in a giant pharmaceutical and food group created by combining the Pharmacia, Procordia and Provendor companies.

headline: Company News; Beacon to Acquire Coleman Division
abstract: LEAD: Beacon International Ltd. of Toronto has agreed to buy the heating and air-conditioning division of the Coleman Company. Terms of the deal were not disclosed. The transaction is scheduled to be completed in early 1990. Beacon International is a subsidiary of the Beacon Capital Corporation.

headline: More Chrysler Cuts Seen by Iacocca
abstract: LEAD: The chairman of the Chrysler Corporation, Lee A. Iacocca, said sluggish car and truck sales might force the company to increase budget cuts beyond a planned $1 billion by the end of 1990. Mr. Iacocca also said additional closings of assembly plants were possible for the nation's third-largest auto maker.

headline: In the Streets of Prague, The Mood Is Victorious
abstract: LEAD: Even before the sun rose this morning, the people of Prague began gathering to celebrate the resignation on Friday of the country's long-entrenched and conservative Communist Party leadership.

headline: Austral Drops Against Dollar
abstract: LEAD: The Government of President Carlos Saul Menem suffered an economic setback today when the Argentine currency lost 27 percent of its value against the dollar in a single day.

headline: Prague Leader Weighs Quitting Amid the Chaos
abstract: LEAD: Prime Minister Ladislav Adamec announced tonight that he would resign if his new Government was not given ''adequate conditions for its work.''

headline: Colombian Vote Due on Drug Extraditions
abstract: LEAD: The Government announced today that it would let the voters decide if suspected drug traffickers wanted in the United States should be extradited.

headline: Ford Doubles Stake In Jaguar as Stocks Fall
abstract: LEAD: The Ford Motor Company snapped up millions of shares in the British luxury car maker Jaguar as stock prices tumbled worldwide, the company disclosed today.

headline: Tosco Looking For a Buyer
abstract: LEAD: The Tosco Corporation placed itself on the selling block, saying it had retained Bear, Stearns & Company to evaluate offers. The Santa Monica, Calif., oil company said it had been approached by three multinational corporations interested in acquiring the concern or its Northern California refinery.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Lithuania Legalizes Rival Parties, Removing Communists' Monopoly
abstract: LEAD: Lithuania became the first Soviet republic to abolish the Communist Party's guaranteed monopoly on power when its parliament voted overwhelmingly today to legalize rival political parties.

headline: Old Standby, the Corner Bar, Falling Victim to New Values
abstract: LEAD: New attitudes about drinking and concerns about liability are leading to dramatic changes in the character of bars across America.

headline: Europe Nears Mergers Pact
abstract: LEAD: The European Community moved closer today to setting a common policy for investigating the big company mergers that are transforming Europe's business landscape.

headline: Preparing to Operate, Polymerix Fills Post
abstract: LEAD: Polymerix Inc., a company that has not yet manufactured its product, has named Gary J. Schantz president and chief operating officer as it moves toward an operational stage.

headline: Read Their Lips! Soviet Legislators Vote No to Proposal for New Sin Taxes
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet legislature approved the 1990 economic plan and budget tonight, but not before overwhelmingly rejecting a proposal to increase the prices of cigarettes, beer and delicacies.

headline: Japan Surplus Plunges 39.4%
abstract: LEAD: Japan's trade surplus plunged 39.4 percent in October, to $4.66 billion, from $7.68 billion a year earlier, the Finance Ministry said today. It was the largest fall ever.

headline: U.F.O. Landing Is Fact, Not Fantasy, the Russians Insist
abstract: LEAD: It is not a joke, nor a hoax, nor a sign of mental instability, nor an attempt to drum up local tourism by drawing the curious, the Soviet press agency Tass insisted today in discussions of what it called an extraterrestrial visit to southern Russia.

headline: Resistance Stirs Among Boat People
abstract: LEAD: With the next forcible return of Vietnamese boat people expected within two weeks, Hong Kong officials disclosed today that refugees inside detention camps here have drawn up resistance plans that include setting fires, arming themselves with homemade weapons and taking hostages.

headline: Vitro to Buy Anchor for $820 Million
abstract: LEAD: Vitro S.A. and the Anchor Glass Container Corporation announced yesterday that they had signed an agreement for Vitro to acquire Anchor in a deal valued at about $820 million. The agreement ends a bitter two-month struggle by Anchor to remain independent.

headline: Values Are the Means and the End
abstract: LEAD: For at least 25 years, we Americans have failed to instill basic values in our children, in the workplace, in government and in many other parts of our society. We are simply not getting across such basic ideas as decency, fair play, courtesy, hard work, scholarship, perseverance, self-confidence, teamwork, discipline and a host of other character traits.

headline: Houghton Mifflin's New Chairman
abstract: LEAD: Harold T. Miller, who helped rally prominent authors to fight an attempted takeover of Houghton Mifflin Inc. in 1979, announced yesterday that he would retire in April as chairman and chief executive of the Boston-based publishing company.

headline: Rebels in Phillipine Army Bomb Aquino Palace and Attack Bases
abstract: LEAD: Rebel troops bombed the presidential palace this morning after attacking three military camps and three broadcast stations in an attempt to overthrow the Government of President Corazon C. Aquino.

headline: Dallas Corp. Deal
abstract: LEAD: The Dallas Corporation, a maker of garage, truck and trailer doors, signed a definitive agreement for the Bessemer Securities Corporation to acquire all outstanding Dallas shares for $24 each in cash, or almost $180 million. Dallas's board of directors has approved the tender offer, which a Bessemer subsidiary said will start by Friday.

headline: 5 CHARGED IN PLOT TO EXPORT ARMS
abstract: LEAD: Three South Africans and two Americans have been charged with trying to export American missile technology illegally to South Africa in a case that raises new questions about military ties between South Africa and Israel, according to Federal law enforcement officials and arrest records made public this week.

headline: Western Union Loses A Credit Line
abstract: LEAD: In what could damage the Western Union Corporation's attempts to revive itself, the Columbia Savings and Loan Association has said it will pull out of a deal to provide an additional $51.4 million to purchase Western Union securities, Brooke Partners L.P. said yesterday.

headline: LEBANESE APPOINT CENTRIST OFFICIAL TO THE PRESIDENCY
abstract: LEAD: Lebanon elected another new President today, replacing the leader killed in an explosion two days ago. But the prospects for an end to 14 years of civil strife seemed as far away as ever.

headline: Soviet Miners Strike in Defiance of Ban
abstract: LEAD: In a powerful challenge to the new Soviet ban on strikes in energy and other crucial industries, thousands of coal miners in the Arctic Circle walked off their jobs today, demanding political and economic changes.

headline: Whittaker Sells A Plastics Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Whittaker Corporation said it had sold its Duall/Wind plastic extrusion business to the American Filtrona Corporation, Richmond, for an undisclosed price. The sale is part of a series of divestitures Whittaker has made under a plan made in response to an unwelcome takeover attempt.

headline: U.N. Plans Summit Talks on Saving Children
abstract: LEAD: A ''world summit for children'' is being planned here next September to mobilize money and resources to save the lives of 50 million children, who the authorities predict would otherwise die in the next decade.

headline: Airlines Cleared of Rigging Their Reservation Systems
abstract: LEAD: A Federal jury ruled on Friday that American Airlines and United Airlines did not monopolize the computerized airline reservations industry through their control of the two largest computer systems that travel agents use to book plane tickets.

headline: A Scrappy New Spirit At Young & Rubicam
abstract: LEAD: Fighting a racketeering indictment and landing on the short end of two highly publicized lawsuits, Young & Rubicam finds itself suffering from a malady its copywriters invented: a king-sized Excedrin headache.

headline: Clamor in the East; The New Europe: Will It Come Apart as It Comes Together?
abstract: LEAD: More than a century ago, the Hapsburg Empire, based in this grand old city on the Danube, stretched across Central and Eastern Europe from the Tyrolian Alps to the Carpathian Mountains.

headline: United Telecom Links Units
abstract: LEAD: United Telecommunications Inc. said yesterday that it would combine its local telephone and long-distance businesses, including the U S Sprint Communications Company.

headline: Indian Police Kill 5 Protesters
abstract: LEAD: The police fired on crowds protesting the arrest of a separatist leader in northern Jammu-Kashmir state, killing at least 5 and wounding 75, officials said. The authorities imposed a curfew and sent soldiers in Anantnag, where three people were killed by police gunfire on Friday, a Government spokesman said.

headline: Bond Brewing Group Put in Receivership
abstract: LEAD: The Supreme Court of the state of Victoria today appointed receivers and managers for brewing interests held by the Bond Corporation Holdings Ltd. of Australia.

headline: Bonwit Sale Move
abstract: LEAD: The L. J. Hooker Corporation said it would seek approval of a Federal Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan to retain Financo Inc. to sell its Bonwit Teller and Sakowitz Inc. specialty stores. Financo is a New York investment banker specializing in mergers and acquisitions. Sanford C. Sigoloff, Hooker's chief executive, said Bonwit Teller continued to show improvement, but ''Hooker management felt that the best way to maximize returns was through a sale.

headline: Morgan Sells 'Junk' Issue
abstract: LEAD: Investment bankers at Morgan Stanley & Company underwrote an $850 million ''junk bond'' offering yesterday. headline: New Delhi Deploying Troops in an Edgy Kashmir
abstract: LEAD: The strategically important Kashmir valley was under curfew for the third day today as the Government moved in troops and put armored personnel carriers on the streets of Srinagar to prevent pro-independence demonstrations.

headline: Pronouncing The Names
abstract: LEAD: SILVIU BRUCAN, an opposition leader: SEEL-vyoo broo-KAHN

headline: Sun Microsystems Sees Gain
abstract: LEAD: Sun Microsystems Inc. said today that it expected a small operating profit in the quarter that ended last Saturday.

headline: Wadi Dahr Journal; Give Up Desert Ways? Not Queen of Sheba's Land
abstract: LEAD: The old is very old here, and the new is very new. Sometimes, the collision is painful.

headline: U.S. Sees Israeli Help in Pretoria's Missile Work
abstract: LEAD: American officials say there are indications from intelligence reports that Israel has helped South Africa developed a medium-range missile.

headline: France and S.E.C. in Inquiries Pact
abstract: LEAD: The Securities and Exchange Commission and its French counterpart signed a cooperative agreement on securities investigations today.

headline: Stronger U.S. Antitrust Action Vowed
abstract: LEAD: In their first major policy statements, President Bush's two top antitrust officials said today that they would strengthen enforcement policies and singled out the airline and health-care industries for scrutiny.

headline: Campbell Soup Family Disbands Voting Trust
abstract: LEAD: Nine descendants of a founder of the Campbell Soup Company, have agreed to disband a family voting trust that controls 26.5 percent of the company's shares.

headline: Contras Turning to Younger Leaders
abstract: LEAD: After eight years of war against the Nicaraguan Government, the contra army commanders in the field have little in common with the English-speaking politicians and C.I.A.-picked veterans of the deposed military dictatorship who once dominated the rebel movement.

headline: German Morning After; The Signs Are Mixed on Whether Reforms Are Closer in East in the Wake of Protests
abstract: LEAD: As the wave of street protests that swept East Germany on its 40th anniversary seems to recede, the question left behind is whether democratic change is any closer.

headline: Irish 'Peace Trains' Halted by Bomb Threat
abstract: LEAD: Two ''peace trains'' that were formed to protest Irish Republican Army bomb attacks on the Dublin-Belfast rail link have been halted by a bomb threat.

headline: Fighting in Panama: United Nations; Council Deadlocked on Panama Rivals
abstract: LEAD: The Security Council remained deadlocked today as it tried to decide the legitimate government of Panama in the aftermath of the United States military strike.

headline: The Trade Deficit Takes Off Again
abstract: LEAD: The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened sharply to $10.2 billion in October, the biggest imbalance in 10 months, as imports reached a record level. The Government also reported that inventories climbed four-tenths of a percent in October, to a seasonally adjusted $793.9 billion. In November, wholesale prices edged down a tenth of a percent and capacity utilization also was down a tenth of a point, to 82.7 percent.

headline: New Cabinet Named in Jordan
abstract: LEAD: Prime Minister Mudar Badran announced the formation of a Cabinet today that excludes the fundamentalist Muslim Brotherhood movement, which makes up the largest bloc in Jordan's new Parliament.

In an Impatient Pocket of Rural India, Gandhi Fights for His Political Future
abstract: LEAD: For the next few weeks, Kamal Bahadur Singh and thousands of people like him in farming villages and towns in a rural pocket of India called Amethi will number among the most important people in Indian politics.

headline: HOMELESS IN CHINA BRAVE COLD WINDS
abstract: LEAD: Thousands of peasants whose homes were destroyed by earthquakes prepared today to spend a second night outdoors on the windy northern Chinese plain.

headline: Expansion Is Planned By Borden
abstract: LEAD: Borden Inc., putting muscle into its move away from the dairy business, said yesterday that it plans to spend $650 million over the next two years to expand and modernize its plants around the world. It will also spend an additional $75 million to $100 million on advertising and marketing.

headline: Regulator Defends Role in Savings Unit Failure
abstract: LEAD: M. Danny Wall, the nation's top savings and loan regulator, today defended his handling of the costliest savings and loan failure to date. He asserted that his office lacked sufficient proof in 1987 that the $6 billion Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif., was insolvent.

headline: Japan Trade Surplus Down
abstract: LEAD: Japan's current account surplus, which measures trade in both goods and services, fell in September for the seventh straight month, tumbling 22 percent from a year earlier, to $5.91 billion, the Finance Ministry said today.

headline: South Brazil Cheers Break In Berlin Wall
abstract: LEAD: Only weeks after Oktoberfest, church steeples here have cause for celebration again: the breach in the Berlin wall.

headline: Greek Conservative Gets Coalition Deadline
abstract: LEAD: Constantine Mitsotakis, leader of the conservative New Demacracy Party, received a presidential go-ahead today to try to form a new government, but party officials say he faces a difficult time.

headline: Treasury to Sell 2-Year and 5-Year Notes
abstract: LEAD: The Treasury's schedule of issues this week includes today's regular weekly auction of three- and six-month bills, tomorrow's sale of two-year notes and Wednesday's sale of five-year notes.

headline: British Trade Deficit Slows
abstract: LEAD: Britain announced today that its foreign trade deficit had narrowed to $:1.54 billion ($2.4 billion) last month.

headline: Calvin Klein Executive To Head Jordache Jeans
abstract: LEAD: David D. Warren has been named president of the Jordache Jeans division of Jordache Enterprises Inc., filling a post that has been vacant since July.

headline: Monsanto Offer
abstract: LEAD: The Monsanto Company is offering $100 million in debentures due 2009 through Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. The 8 7/8 percent debentures were priced at 99.85 to yield 9 percent, or about 11 basis points more than the Treasury's 30-year bond issue. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.

headline: Data General Sets Move and Layoffs
abstract: LEAD: The Data General Corporation, a Westboro-based computer maker, said it would sell its plant in Portsmouth, N.H., and move manufacturing operations to a larger plant in Apex, N.C., in the next year. The company said it would eliminate 2,200 of 14,200 jobs and that more than 700 people would be affected immediately.

headline: Bondholder Pact Is Set By Resorts
abstract: LEAD: Resorts International Inc. confirmed yesterday that it had reached an agreement over the weekend with its bondholder groups intended to allow the troubled casino company to reorganize after a brief period under bankruptcy protection.

headline: WCRS Sets Big Shift to Media Buying
abstract: LEAD: THE British advertising company whose holdings include the American agency Della Femina, McNamee WCRS, yesterday substantially withdrew from the advertising business while at the same time acquiring complete control of the largest media-buying company in Europe.

headline: To Woo Soviet Jews to Israel, A $2 Billion Drive Is Mounted
abstract: LEAD: The Jewish Agency announced a campaign today to raise $2 billion by 1993 to help attract Soviet Jews to Israel and absorb them into society with new housing, education and job training programs.

headline: Tinker Looks Beyond 'USA Today on TV'
abstract: LEAD: GTG Entertainment, the production company formed by Grant A. Tinker and the Gannett Company almost three years ago, has yet to come up with a hit program, although it has taken several hits itself.

headline: Fighting in the East: Washington; Baker Gives U.S. Approval If Soviets Act on Rumania
abstract: LEAD: Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d said today that the United States would approve if the Soviet Union or other Warsaw Pact nations decided to send troops into Rumania to support the pro-democracy forces trying to assume control in Bucharest.

headline: White House Adds $200 Million to Polish Aid Plan
abstract: LEAD: Under pressure from Democratic lawmakers to respond more aggressively to the changes in Eastern Europe, the White House announced today that President Bush would ask Congress for an additional $200 million in economic aid for Poland.

headline: Re-evaluation Is Urged on Cutting High-Tech Aid
abstract: LEAD: Officials in the White House who favor a Government pullback from financing advanced military research and development programs with commercial applications may need to re-evaluate their position because of the needs of high-technology industries and the political climate, a number of economists and legislators said today.

headline: East-Bloc Is Said to Cut Managua Aid
abstract: LEAD: Two weeks after the State Department asserted that the Soviet bloc had increased arms shipments to Nicaragua, American intelligence officials have concluded that shipments have instead declined by about 20 percent this year, Administration officials said today.

headline: From Cash Cow To Cash Machine
abstract: LEAD: Romeo J. Ventres knows exactly what he wants Borden Inc. to be when he retires in December 1991. He wants it to be the lowest-cost producer of all its products, from milk to pasta to plastics to glue. He wants it to have a decent mix of national and regional brands. He certainly wants it to be independent - a year ago, he and Borden's top 25 managers agreed to quit simultaneously in the event of a hostile takeover.

headline: Grenade Explodes in Bogota, Killing the Man Carrying It
abstract: LEAD: A man was killed today when a grenade he was carrying exploded near Colombia's congress building a few hours after the introduction of a guerrilla amnesty bill that excludes pardons for drug traffickers, the police said.

headline: New Politburo in East Germany
abstract: LEAD:  Egon Krenz, 52, Politburo member since 1983, was responsible for security matters until he became General Secretary on Oct. 18. Son of a tailor, he joined the party in 1955 and attended a party school in Moscow between 1964 and 1967. For many years led the Communist youth organization. Retained seat.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Farmers, Fearing a Drop in Prices, Criticize Poland's Economic Plan
abstract: LEAD: The far-reaching economic program of the Solidarity-led Government came under attack today from farmers' representatives, who said they preferred guaranteed minimum prices to the risks of a free market.
