headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Advertising's Funniest
abstract: LEAD: An art director edged out several copywriters to win the ''Funniest Person in Advertising'' contest on Monday. Helene A. Cohn of Geer, DuBois won the competition, sponsored by Stand-Up New York, a comedy club. After six weeks of preliminary rounds, Miss Cohn defeated 30 other contestants to win a booking at Stand-Up New York and an appearance on the syndicated television program ''Everyday With Joan Lunden.

headline: Penrod's Rigs Attract Rowan
abstract: LEAD: The Rowan Companies, a Houston-based contract drilling company, said today that it had expressed an interest in acquiring the rigs of the Penrod Drilling Corporation, a larger drilling company owned jointly by the Hunt brothers' family estates and a group of banks led by the Manufacturers Hanover Trust Company.

headline: A MEXICAN RELIC IS BURIED AT LAST
abstract: LEAD: After nearly 75 years, one of the most grisly relics of the Mexican Revolution has finally been laid to rest. But the interment of what remained of the right arm of General Alvaro Obregon is not likely to erase the talismanic qualities Mexicans have long associated with both the limb and the man.

headline: Hong Kong to Push for Rights as Britons
abstract: LEAD: Hong Kong politicians and citizen groups vowed today to press their fight to force Britain to open its doors to all its colonial subjects here and grant them full British passports before the colony is handed back to China in 1997.

headline: Taiwan Draws Investors
abstract: LEAD: New securities firms and investors are continuing to enter Taiwan's vibrant stock market, the country's Securities and Exchange Comission said today. The commission said Taiwan, with 20 million people, would have 4 million stock investor accounts by the end of 1989, against 3.7 million now and 700,000 in May 1988.

headline: Housing Agency Is Established
abstract: LEAD: The savings and loan industry's largest trade group today announced the formation of a foundation to encourage savings institutions to make more housing loans to people of modest means.

headline: Egypt Reportedly Lists 12 Palestinians for Talks
abstract: LEAD: Egypt, backed by the P.L.O., has put forward the names of 12 Palestinians to sit at the negotiating table in peace talks between Palestinians and Israelis, Palestinians here said today.

headline: To Briton, a Play's the Thing, but Who Pays?
abstract: LEAD: What do you say to a complete stranger who brazenly accosts you, tells you that his name is Neal Foster and that he wants you to donate your free time to help him raise money? If your name is Jack Lemmon, Dustin Hoffman, Alan Bennett or Dame Judi Dench, you say yes.

headline: Hilton Sale Hits Snag; Stock Falls
abstract: LEAD: The shares of the Hilton Hotels Corporation fell sharply today amid fears that the company might not be sold after more than four months on the block.

headline: Apple Is Said To Settle Suit
abstract: LEAD: Apple Computer Inc. agreed to settle a patent-infringement lawsuit filed against it by Quickview Systems Inc., people close to the industry said.

headline: U.S. AIDES CRITICAL OF BRITAIN'S MOVE
abstract: LEAD: The Administration and Congressional leaders today criticized as unacceptable Britain's forced repatriation of Vietnamese refugees from Hong Kong.

headline: Sogo Weighs Buying Saks
abstract: LEAD: The Sogo Company, a Japanese department store concern, is considering acquiring the New York-based retail chain Saks Fifth Avenue, a Sogo spokesman said last week.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * American Federal Savings Bank, Jacksonville, Fla., named Norman J. Harrison chief executive.

headline: Upheaval in the East; In Face of Protests, East German Sports Leaders Agree to Resign, Papers Report
abstract: LEAD: The political reforms sweeping across East Germany at breath-taking speed have apparently caught up to the nation's vaunted sports system.

headline: Stocks Are Mixed in Very Slow Trading
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices ended narrowly mixed yesterday in extremely slow post-Christmas trading. The Dow Jones industrial average slipped 2.13 points, to 2,709.26, but advances on the New York Stock Exchange edged out declines by 712 to 664.

headline: EXECUTIVES
abstract: LEAD: * Curtice Burns Foods, Rochester, which processes and markets food products, named Darryl L. Canfield corporate controller.

headline: Publishing
abstract: LEAD: SINCE shortly after the Frankfurt Book Fair began in 1949, it has been the most important annual gathering for the book publishing world. This year's fair, which ends today, attracted many American publishers, but their reasons for attending are much different from what they were only a decade ago.

headline: The Emigres' Voices
abstract: LEAD: For East Germans now in the West, individual tales testify to difficult times and personal dramas emerged from the chorus of cheers. Page A6.

headline: People
abstract: LEAD: * Rick Flata has been named senior vice president and media director of Hill, Holliday, Connors & Cosmopulos/New York.

headline: Thorn EMI's Strategy
abstract: LEAD: Thorn EMI P.L.C., the British music and electronics company, said on Friday that it was looking for possible joint ventures and mergers for its military electronics unit after failing to find a buyer in the last five months. A Thorn spokesman, Colin Woodley, said the company had not received an offer that ''reflects the true value of the business.

headline: France to End Controls On Foreign Exchange
abstract: LEAD: France announced today that it would abolish its remaining foreign exchange controls beginning Jan. 1. The controls have been in place for 44 years.

headline: Montevideo Journal; Basques Have Lots to Boast of (and at Times Do)
abstract: LEAD: From the crack of bare hands driving the ball across the fronton court to the waitresses in green and red serving garlic-laden dishes, a modest downtown club is trying to keep alive an identity brought from the distant Pyrenees.

headline: Deng Warns Against Own Senility
abstract: LEAD: China's senior leader, Deng Xiaoping, told a small group of top officials that they should not listen to him if he starts to say ''crazy things'' as he gets older and becomes less clear-minded, according to a transcript of a speech he made in September.

headline: EXECUTIVES
abstract: LEAD: * Ameritrust Co., Cleveland, a financial services concern, promoted Frank I. Harding to president and chief executive of its trust and investment management group.

headline: China Says Taiwan Is 'Buying Hearts' Abroad
abstract: LEAD: China has accused Taiwan of using its wealth to buy diplomatic recognition with foreign countries, as a new quarrel further strained relations across the Taiwan Strait.

headline: Donnelley Develops a Way for Magazines to Get Personal
abstract: LEAD: Gutenberg he is not, but, oh! can Fred Clarke move type.

headline: IN QUOTES
abstract: LEAD: ''I'm sure the President is not going to be willing to submit to all that extraneous material in the deficit package just to get capital gains.''   Senator John H. Chaffee,   Republican of Rhode Island.

headline: After the Summit; Gorbachev Said to Seek End To Naval Nuclear Weapons
abstract: LEAD: President Mikhail S. Gorbachev proposed eliminating tactical nuclear weapons from the American and Soviet Navies in his Malta summit meeting with President Bush, Administration officials disclosed today.

headline: FINANCE BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD:  Common Stock

headline: Clamor in the East; No Israeli Ties Yet, Poles Say
abstract: LEAD: Poland today denied an Israeli report that it had decided to restore full diplomatic relations with the Government in Jerusalem. ''The information is not true,'' Deputy Foreign Minister Jan Majewski said. ''The Polish Government is considering the possibility of restoring diplomatic relations with Israel in the not-too-distant future, but it has not taken any decision yet.

headline: Philips Industries Accepts New Bid
abstract: LEAD: Philips Industries, a maker of components for the building and transportation industries, agreed to a new lower price of $24 a share in its proposed buyout by members of management and Merrill Lynch & Company. Philips had originally agreed to be acquired for $25.50 a share. The company's shares rose $1 today, to $23.125, on the New York Stock

headline: Market Place; Foreign Events Shake Up Funds
abstract: LEAD: AS bullets were flying around the presidential palace in Manila last week, nervous investors were selling shares of the fledgling First Philippine Fund, a closed-end mutual fund.

headline: Pretoria May Be Looking to Freed Blacks for Aid
abstract: LEAD: In its treatment of the eight political prisoners released on Sunday, the white minority Government appears to be sending signals that it wants the cooperation of the freed men in promoting some form of negotiations with this country's black majority.

headline: Fed Seen Delaying Lower Rates
abstract: LEAD: Credit market analysts predict that the Federal Reserve Board will not move quickly to lower interest rates, despite fresh signs of economic weakness.

headline: Apple Bancorp Proxy Fight
abstract: LEAD: A New York real estate developer, Stanley Stahl, who holds a 30.3 percent stake in Apple Bancorp Inc., said today that he planned to wage a proxy fight for control of the New York City-based savings bank holding company.

headline: Careers; Arboretum Directors Are Sought
abstract: LEAD: MORE than $150 million is being spent to build arboretums and conservatories, and job opportunties are sure to follow, said Anne L. Crammond, executive director of the Atlanta Botanical Garden.

headline: General Electric's Hungarian Deal
abstract: LEAD: G.E. is moving into Hungary, taking advantage of liberalization in Eastern Europe. General Electric will pay $150 million for control of the Tungsram Company, a light-bulb maker. The deal is the largest American investment in Hungary since World War II. John F. Welch, G.E.'s chairman, said the purchase would help bolster G.E.

headline: Brach's Seeks Use Of Foreign Sugar
abstract: LEAD: The candy maker E. J. Brach & Sons said that unless it was allowed to use less expensive foreign sugar for its candies, it might lay off 3,500 workers and shut down or relocate a 65-year-old Chicago plant. Brach's, which was taken over three years ago by Jacobs Suchard A.G. of Switzerland, has petitioned the Federal

headline: Whittle Plans TV Service In Doctors' Waiting Rooms
abstract: LEAD: Whittle Communications plans to offer television programs specially created for 100,000 doctors' waiting rooms across the nation.

headline: HomeFed to Lift Loan-Loss Fund
abstract: LEAD: The HomeFed Corporation, parent company of the HomeFed Bank, said it will add $115 million to its loan-loss provisions in the fourth quarter. ''These general allowances will provide HomeFed greater flexibility to reduce its level of nonperforming assets and restructure its loan and real estate portfolios,'' said Kim Fletcher, chairman of the San Diego-based savings and loan association.

headline: Market Place; Single Arbitration Agency Is Sought
abstract: LEAD: THE Securities Industry Association has called on Wall Street to set up a single industrywide agency to handle the arbitration of customer disputes, rather than continuing to maintain separate programs at various exchanges and at the National Association of Securities Dealers.

headline: Blighted Buildings Renovated in Bedford-Stuyvesant
abstract: LEAD: Boarded buildings and rubble-strewn lots are widespread in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, but neighborhoods that appear mired in deterioration to some are offering redevelopment opportunities to others.

headline: Swiss Vote Cheers Critics of Army
abstract: LEAD: The outcome of a recent referendum, in which an unexpectedly large minority voted in favor of abolishing the army, has unsettled the Swiss military establishment and heartened those pushing for a reduction of the military budget and other changes.

headline: Economic Calendar
abstract: LEAD: Below are the major economic indicators to be released this week.  Monday  None  Tuesday  Durable Goods Sept.  Auto Sales Mid-Oct.  Wednesday  None  Thursday  G.N.P. 3d Qtr.  Friday  Personal Income Sept.

headline: Bush Gamble With Beijing
abstract: LEAD: Hunkering down against growing criticism of President Bush's diplomatic overture to Beijing, Administration officials said today that the surprise weekend mission was a ''calculated gamble'' taken by a President who considers himself his own China expert.

headline: Journal of Commerce by Fax
abstract: LEAD: The Journal of Commerce on Monday began facsimile transmission of a summary of the next day's paper that reaches subscribers in midafternoon.

headline: Economic Miracle
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS:Advertising; 'Jump' Stays, Slogan Shifts For Toyota
abstract: LEAD: MOST television viewers are quite familiar with the ''Toyota jump,'' the leap of enthusiasm performed by Toyota owners at the end of commercials for the Japanese cars and trucks.

headline: Management Shifts Set By LaSalle Partners
abstract: LEAD: LaSalle Partners, a major real estate owner and manager, announced yesterday that its chairman and founder, William D. Sanders, will become chairman emeritus at age 47, while Stuart L. Scott and C. Gary Gerst will become co-chairmen, effective Jan. 1.

headline: Chairman of 3 Units Named by Forstmann
abstract: LEAD: Forstmann, Little & Company, a leveraged buyout firm, has hired William J. Turner as chairman and chief executive of three of its companies: FL Industries, Lear Siegler Inc. and the FL Aerospace Corporation.

headline: U.S.-Soviet Makers Plan Supersonic Business Jet
abstract: LEAD: In a striking example of commercial glasnost, a Soviet state enterprise that made the planes that bombed Afghanistan has joined an American company to build the ultimate capitalist status symbol: a supersonic jet for business executives.

headline: Economic Scene; Sony Wishes Upon a Star
abstract: LEAD: ARE the services of Peter Guber and Jon Peters, co-chairmen of Columbia Pictures, the Sony Corporation's latest venture into the entertainment business, really worth a half-billion dollars?

headline: Struggle Within the Military Appears to Be a Major Cause
abstract: LEAD: A bitter power struggle between rebellious junior officers and older members of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's inner circle appears to have been a major catalyst in the fighting that erupted in Panama yesterday, experts on Panamanian military affairs say.

headline: Czechs Stream Into Vienna, to Look, Not Buy
abstract: LEAD: On the first weekend day since the Prague authorities eased travel restrictions, more than 100,000 Czechoslovaks streamed into Austria today, mostly on one-day shopping sprees here in the capital, in Linz and in Salzburg.

headline: Kodak Charge Cuts Earnings
abstract: LEAD: In a development that came as little surprise to the financial community, the Eastman Kodak Company said yesterday that it would reduce its fourth-quarter earnings by $273 million, or 85 cents a share, because of write-offs of assets in discontinued businesses and payments to employees who are losing their jobs.

headline: The Malta Summit; East Berlin Amends Constitution, Loosening Communist Hold
abstract: LEAD: East Germany's Parliament amended the country's Constitution today, eliminating the clause that assigned the leading political role to the Communist Party.

headline: Fighting in Panama; Secret U.S. Fighter Jet Is Tried Out in Panama
abstract: LEAD: The United States used its radar-evading F-117 'Stealth fighter-bomber for the first time in the Panama invasion this week, the Defense Department said tonight.

headline: American Savings Delays Voting on a Shift in Charter
abstract: LEAD: Facing strong opposition from shareholders, the management of the American Savings Bank yesterday delayed until Dec. 20 a special meeting of stockholders to vote on converting the bank from a Federal to a state charter.

headline: In Wittenberg, Cries for New Reformation on Date of Old One
abstract: LEAD: It was difficult to imagine what Martin Luther, lying in his tomb under the cold stone floor, might have thought of the throng that packed every medieval inch of the castle church on the anniversary of the day in 1517 when he tacked his 95 theses to the door and so began the Reformation.

headline: Cuba Says Americans Fired on Sentry Posts
abstract: LEAD: Soldiers at the United States Navy base at Guantanamo, Cuba, fired two shots today at Cuban sentry posts, the official news agency Prensa Latina said. It said the shots broke glass but caused no injuries.

headline: Upheaval in the East; GORBACHEV WINS VOTE ON ECONOMY

abstract: LEAD: Pacific Telesis Group, one of the nation's seven regional telephone companies, said that the Oct. 17 earthquake in nothern California had caused $40 million to $50 million in damage to its buildings and network facilities. abstract: LEAD: Israeli leaders agreed today to seek additional pledges of American support as a condition for accepting a United States proposal for Israeli-Palestinian talks in Cairo, political analysts said.

abstract: LEAD: William S. Antle 3d, who six months ago started a concern that helps companies improve their performance, has become president and chief executive of Oak Industries. His mission is to return the San Diego company to profitability.

abstract: LEAD: In an announcement that took Wall Street analysts by surprise, Texas Instruments Inc. said today that it would record a special charge of $55 million against its fourth-quarter profits and would eliminate 1,500 jobs.

abstract: LEAD: China's senior leader, Deng Xiaoping, meeting the first high-level American officials to visit here since the June killings in Tiananmen Square, said today that the two countries must restore and improve their strained relations in the interest of world stability.

It compared with an 18.3 percent rise in the 12 months ended in September and a 25 percent rise in the 12 months to October 1988.

abstract: LEAD: Every few weeks, a heavily laden plane flies from Iran to Syria with a cargo of weapons, food and other supplies. The material is then trucked across the border and distributed to various Shiite terrorist groups in Lebanon.

abstract: LEAD: A state court judge in Massachusetts has dismissed a lawsuit by a group of former stockholders of The Atlantic magazine who contended that Mortimer B. Zuckerman owed them additional payments from his acquisition of the publication in 1980.

abstract: LEAD: The Rumanian press has begun reporting events with a candor unthinkable before the ouster of Nicolae Ceausescu, Following are excerpts from the Rumanian press agency Agerpres and Rumanian, East German and Hungarian broadcasts as monitored and translated by the United States Government's Foreign Broadcast Information Service.

abstract: LEAD: East Germany's Communist Party met in an emergency congress this morning and debated its own survival, nominating a lawyer as its new chairman.

headline: Planner for Pan Am Heads Commuter Unit
abstract: LEAD: Pan Am Express, the commuter subsidiary of Pan American World Airways, has named William R. Lange president and chief operating officer.

headline: G.E. to Eliminate 450 Appliance Jobs
abstract: LEAD: The General Electric Company said it would eliminate about 450 jobs in the next three years in the home laundry manufacturing operations at its major appliance plant here. G.E. said it would shift some manufacturing work to subcontractors to cut costs. The affected jobs will be eliminated through attrition.

headline: Lockheed Division To Reduce Jobs
abstract: LEAD: The Lockheed Aeronautical Systems Company, a unit of the Lockheed Corporation, will cut several hundred jobs in the next two months as part of the company''s cost control program, a spokesman said.

headline: Cadence to Buy Gateway Design
abstract: LEAD: Cadence Design Systems Inc. agreed to buy the Gateway Design Automation Corporation of Lowell, Mass., for stock valued at more than $72 million. Cadence, a growing supplier of software for the design of integrated circuits, reported sales of $67.1 million last year.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Ceausescu Blames 'Fascists' For Uproar in Rumania City
abstract: LEAD: The Rumanian President, Nicolae Ceausescu, speaking to his nation for the first time since security forces cracked down on tens of thousands of protesters in a western Rumanian city Sunday, said tonight that the demonstrations had been the work of ''fascist reactionary groups.''

headline: PRESIDENT CALLS PANAMA SLAYING A GREAT OUTRAGE
abstract: LEAD: President Bush today called the weekend slaying of an American Marine officer by Panamanian soldiers ''an enormous outrage.'' With tensions high, a United States military officer in Panama City wounded a uniformed Panamanian a few hours after the President spoke.

headline: Cowles Sale Of 2 Papers
abstract: LEAD: The Cowles Media Company said today that it would sell The Rapid City Journal in South Dakota and The Great Falls Tribune in Montana and would offer to buy back up to 250,000 shares.

headline: Colgate-Palmolive To Acquire Vipont
abstract: LEAD: The Colgate-Palmolive Company will acquire Vipont Pharmaceutical Inc. for about $94 million, enabling Colgate to strengthen its oral hygiene product line. The merger agreement calls for Vipont, based in Fort Collins, to sell Colgate all of its outstanding common shares, at $14 a share. Vipont will also spin off to its shareholders on Dec.

headline: Eastern to Cut Some Flights in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: Eastern Airlines, which just sold its Latin American routes, is also cutting back some domestic flights, including nonstop service from Miami to Boston, Philadelphia, Orlando and Tampa, Fla., and several Caribbean cities, the company said today.

headline: Miniscribe Layoffs
abstract: LEAD: The Miniscribe Corporation said it will take a $40 million restructuring charge in its current quarter. The company said the first step in its restructuring included the layoff of 110 employees. It said it expects to lay off more employees at the beginning of March. Miniscribe, a maker of disk drives for microcomputer systems, also said that once the restructuring was completed its Longmont headquarters would house only administrative and sales operations and all final assembly of products would be done at a plant in Singapore.

headline: Hazards in Arms Cuts, NATO Chief Warns
abstract: LEAD: The Secretary General of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization warned Western allies today that it was ''wrong and dangerous'' for them to take independent steps toward disarmament in response to the process of change in the Soviet bloc.

headline: Mandela Lives Without Regrets, His Son Reports
abstract: LEAD: In this dusty farm town lost among the rolling green hills of the Transkei homeland, a shopkeeper awaits the release of a father who has passed 10,000 days in captivity.

headline: 301 Chinese Expelled by Japan
abstract: LEAD: In the first of what is expected to be a series of transfers, the Japanese Government said today that it would return 301 Chinese who sailed here over the summer falsely claiming to be Vietnamese refugees and seeking to resettle in Japan.

headline: Mortgage Rates Drop
abstract: LEAD: Fixed-rate home mortgages are averaging 9.95 percent, according to a national survey released today by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation.

headline: Fears Expressed for 40 East Timor Protesters
abstract: LEAD: Amnesty International expressed concern today for the safety of about 40 people in East Timor said to have been arrested for taking part in a pro-independence protest in front of Pope John Paul II last week when he visited the disputed Indonesian province.

headline: Hopeful of New Cancer Treatments, Companies Team Up to Study a Gene
abstract: LEAD: A day after two researchers at the University of California at San Francisco received the Nobel Prize for the discovery of normal genes that can cause cancer when they go awry, a tiny New York biotechnology company received the first Food and Drug Administration approval for a diagnostic test based on such genes.

headline: East German Communists Confront Party's Collapse
abstract: LEAD: Confusion and insecurity reigned in East German politics today as the Communist Party struggled to redefine its role and new parties tried to take form.

headline: U.S. SAYS LASERS STRIKE ITS PLANES
abstract: LEAD: The Pentagon said today that Soviet ships were suspected of aiming laser beams at four American military aircraft in the Pacific, possibly injuring an eye of one crewman.

headline: Senate Votes 6 Pacts To Track Drug Money
abstract: LEAD: Despite objections raised by some Republicans over the past two years, the Senate approved treaties today that are intended to help American investigators track money laundering and prosecute drug traffickers in six countries.

abstract: LEAD: The Treasury's schedule of issues this week is active, beginning with today's regular weekly auction of three- and six-month bills and continuing with an auction of $10 billion in two-year bills tomorrow.

headline: Mighty German Banks Face Curb
abstract: LEAD: West Germany's commercial banks have long been accused of having too much power over the nation's industry and financial markets. They sit on the boards of almost every major West German company, they own big stakes in many large corporations and they dominate trading on the nation's securities markets.

headline: Shearson Announces Cash Plan
abstract: LEAD: Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and the American Express Company announced a plan yesterday to raise badly needed cash for the brokerage firm by selling assets and issuing new stock and debt.

headline: Suit Is Filed By Ferranti
abstract: LEAD: The British military electronics company Ferranti, which has said it was victimized by fraud in its United States operations, said today that it had filed a lawsuit seeking nearly $400 million from former employees and associated companies.

headline: Death Toll Spurring Spanish Draft Resistance
abstract: LEAD: When the grim figures are announced each year, the Spanish Defense Ministry invariably tries to blame bad driving and personal problems for the large number of young Spaniards who die or commit suicide while doing military service.

headline: How the Brazilian Leftist Surged: With TV
abstract: LEAD: Television, which electronically binds this sprawling nation together, is a major factor behind the sudden surge of a leftist candidate in Brazil's presidential race, analysts here say.

headline: Exchanges' Computers Overcome the Volume
abstract: LEAD: Crushing volume in the first hours of trading on the nation's financial exchanges yesterday gave the new computer systems their first test in live trading. And industry officials said the systems in the various exchanges, put in place after the Oct. 19, 1987, market crash, held up with only minor problems.

headline: Factory Orders Advanced 2.9% in August
abstract: LEAD: Orders to American factories for manufactured goods rose 2.9 percent in August, the Government said today. But analysts said a one-month increase from automobile orders belied weakness in the industrial sector.

headline: Goodbye Rubles, Hello Baubles: Russians Rush to Get Rid of Cash
abstract: LEAD: The people standing three deep in line today in front of the jewelry store on the Arbat pedestrian mall did not need the official announcement on Wednesday that the exchange rate for the ruble would be slashed to know the waning value of their currency.

abstract: LEAD:  General Assembly  Meets at 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.  ECONOMIC AND FINANCIAL COMMITTEE - 3 P.M.  DECOLONIZATION COMMITTEE - 3 P.M.  ADMINISTRATIVE AND BUDGETARY COMMITTEE - 3 P.M.  LEGAL COMMITTEE - 10 A.M.

headline: U.S. Critical on Export
abstract: LEAD: Venezuela is subsidizing exports of aluminum sulfate and selling it in the United States at less than fair value, the Commerce Department said today. It said that if the International Trade Commission finds that the shipments have injured the United States industry, countervailing duties would be imposed.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST: SATURDAY, DECEMBER 2, 1989
abstract: LEAD:  Markets

headline: Building a 'Flying Train': U.S. Interest Grows, but Others Are Ahead
abstract: LEAD: Visions of trains riding fast-moving magnetic fields instead of scraping along rails have fascinated scientists for decades. Now the Federal Government, which killed its first research programs for such ''flying trains'' in 1975, is reconsidering its approach. Manufacturers looking for new markets have formed a coalition to press for research money in the field.

headline: IN QUOTES
abstract: LEAD: ''The study means that narcotics is one of America's major industries, right up there with consumer electronics, automobiles and steelmaking.''   Robert B. Reich,   Harvard professor,   on a Federal study putting the cost   of drug abuse at $60 billion a year.

headline: U.S. CONSIDERED AID TO PANAMA REBELS
abstract: LEAD: The White House considered military support for the Panamanian uprising but ruled it out because it was uneasy with the rebel leadership, fearful of a trap and uncertain whether Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega had been captured, Administration officials said today.

headline: Pledge Sought On Oil Rights
abstract: LEAD: Oil companies should be guaranteed the right to produce oil they find in authorized offshore explorations, Ken T. Derr, the chairman of the Chevron Corporation, said Thursday.

headline: Debate on 'Dollarization' Is Growing in Argentina
abstract: LEAD: The return of runaway inflation and the collapse in value of the national currency have opened a growing public debate over whether Argentina should simply adopt the United States dollar as its money.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  International

headline: Viacom to Sell a 50% Stake In Showtime TV Service
abstract: LEAD: Viacom Inc. said yesterday that it had agreed to sell a 50 percent stake in Showtime, the nation's second-largest pay television service, to Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's largest cable operator, for $225 million.

headline: Anglican Head Prays With the Pope in Rome
abstract: LEAD: Making his first official visit to the Vatican, the Archbishop of Canterbury prayed alongside Pope John Paul II today as the two spiritual leaders discussed future reunification of the Roman Catholic and Anglican churches.

headline: FINANCE BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: Golden Nugget's Roll of the Dice
abstract: LEAD: Even along the gaudy Strip, with its pulsating neon, attention-grabbing architecture and innumerable exhortations to try one's luck, Golden Nugget Inc.'s new hotel-casino, the Mirage, will be hard to miss.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  The Economy

headline: Crane Seeking Milton Roy
abstract: LEAD: The Crane Company said today that it would like to acquire the Milton Roy Company, a maker of analytic instruments and pumps, for $21 a share in cash, prompting a sharp rise in the St. Petersburg, Fla.. company's shares on the New York Stock Exchange.

headline: Little Chance Seen for Bills That Would Put Rein on Fed
abstract: LEAD: This month, Congress plans to take its first close look in years at how the Federal Reserve makes economic policy. Two competing measures introduced by House Democrats, one supported and the other strongly opposed by the Fed, would in totally different ways assert political influence over the powerful, secretive institution.

headline: Salvador Army Is Said to Seize Rebel Positions
abstract: LEAD: Heavy Salvadoran Army counterattacks today and Tuesday night appear to have routed leftist guerrillas from several strongholds on the outskirts of this city.

headline: U.S. Officials Look to Policy on East Germany as Next Big Challenge
abstract: LEAD: The Bush Administration is reviewing American policy toward East Germany, seeking a balance of encouraging democratization there without also fostering a pell-mell movement toward reunification of Germany that would threaten both Moscow and America's NATO allies.

headline: U.S. Car Sales Dropped 2.5% In Final 10 Days of October
abstract: LEAD: Sales of domestically built cars fell by 2.5 percent in late October and those of light trucks fell by 3.4 percent, as the steep sales declines of earlier last month began to moderate.

headline: Apple Strays From Mass Appeal
abstract: LEAD: From the time it decided to sound friendly by naming itself after a fruit, Apple Computer Inc. has proclaimed that its corporate mission is to spread computers to the masses.

headline: Trump Has Some Wall St. Believers
abstract: LEAD: Although Donald J. Trump arouses considerable skepticism among Wall Street stock traders, a minority is starting to take seriously his offer to buy the AMR Corporation, the parent of American Airlines, for $7.5 billion in cash.

headline: 20 Papers in Britain Agree to an Ethics Code
abstract: LEAD: Hoping to head off more Government restrictions and to rebuild public trust in their industry, editors of 20 national newspapers in Britain have agreed to an ethics code and a system to deal with complaints.

headline: Rights Unit Accuses U.S. on Salvador
abstract: LEAD: Americas Watch, a New York-based human rights organization, has accused the Bush Administration of trying to cover up abuses by the Salvadoran Army during this month's offensive by guerrillas.

headline: Hard Facts Daunt Israeli Researcher
abstract: LEAD: As Meron Benvenisti sees it, Israelis of both the left and the right refuse to allow the facts to get in the way.

headline: East Germany Revamping and Taking the Politics Out of Its Army
abstract: LEAD: The 176,000-member National People's Army, like other institutions here, is being thoroughly reshaped as a result of the upheavals in the Communist leadership that began six weeks ago.

headline: Canada Invites Bids for Oil Rights in Arctic
abstract: LEAD: For the first time in nearly two decades, the Canadian Government is inviting petroleum companies that had not previously explored for oil in the Arctic Ocean to do so.

headline: COMMUNIST PARTY IN HUNGARY VOTES FOR RADICAL SHIFT
abstract: LEAD: The Hungarian Communist Party voted today to transform itself into a socialist party and said it would strive to bridge the gulf between doctrinaire Marxism and European democratic socialism.

headline: SOVIET URGES END OF MILITARY PACTS
abstract: LEAD: Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze struck a familiar refrain of Soviet European policy today by calling for a phasing out of Eastern and Western military alliances. He spoke as the foreign ministers of the Warsaw Pact began a two-day meeting here.

headline: Pope, on Delicate Ground, Visits Indonesia
abstract: LEAD: Pope John Paul II brought a message of Roman Catholic kinship and loyalty to Indonesia today as he began a diplomatically delicate visit to the world's most populous Muslim country.

headline: Upheaval in the East: Tass; Reports From the Rumanian Capital by Correspondents for Tass
abstract: LEAD: Until today, Western journalists were not allowed into Rumania. Here are dispatches on the situation in Rumania yesterday from Bucharest correspondents for the Soviet press agency, Tass, which translated the reports.  'The Army Is With Us!'

headline: Bank Funds And C.D.'s Up
abstract: LEAD: Yields on certificates of deposit and money market accounts at commercial banks and savings institutions were generally higher in the week that ended yesterday.

headline: Unocal to Close Texas Refinery
abstract: LEAD: The Unocal Corporation said it would suspend operations at its refinery here next year because the plant, built in 1924, is no longer profitable. The operation, 45 miles northeast of Houston, has 462 employees, including 337 represented by labor unions, according to a statement from the Los Angeles-based company.

headline: Wild Greenwich Tract Being Divided Into Lots
abstract: LEAD: The last of the great private estates that helped give Greenwich, Conn., its patrician character - a 169-acre wilderness area in the town's northwest corner - has been sold and the first phase of subdividing it has been approved.

headline: Grey Earnings Up
abstract: LEAD: Grey Advertising said its third-quarter earnings rose 7.6 percent, to $2.41 million, or $1.95 a share, from $2.24 million, or $1.65, in the comparable 1988 quarter. Revenues rose 14 percent, to $97.15 million, from $85.20 million.

headline: Man in the News; V.P. SINGH: LOW-KEY INDIAN IN HIGH-ANXIETY JOB
abstract: LEAD: Vishwanath Pratap Singh, chosen on Friday by the centrist National Front to lead its Government, brings a low-key, efficient work style honed by decades of political experience that contrasts with the aggressive, high-profile personality of his predecessor, Rajiv Gandhi.

headline: Amgen to Give Drug to Needy
abstract: LEAD: Amgen Inc. said this week that it would give free supplies of genetically engineered erythropoietin to several thousand kidney dialysis patients who do not have Government or private health insurance.

headline: Boeing's Fight Over Bonuses
abstract: LEAD: The issue at the heart of the Boeing Company strike, which has idled 58,000 workers for more than a week, is a new one in the American labor movement - one that is forcing union leaders to confront not only management but also their own members.

headline: Bombing Attempt in London
abstract: LEAD: A bomb apparently intended for a British general was found under a car, and the police said today that it appeared to be the work of the Irish Republican Army. The bomb was placed under the wrong car and fell off because it was not attached properly, the authorities said.

headline: Beijing Plan for Hong Kong Dims Hopes for a Democracy
abstract: LEAD: Hong Kong's hopes to establish a democratic government after it reverts to Beijing's authority were diminished today when China declared that only one-third of the post-1997 legislature would be directly elected.

headline: Don't Give Up on Junk Bonds
abstract: LEAD: RECENTLY, I participated on a panel with leaders of the House and Senate to discuss mechanisms for increasing investment in distressed communities. None of the communities or minority businesses we discussed were investment grade. Rather, they were completely unbankable, and most credit analyses by rating agencies would classify them as ''junk'' investments.

headline: Stocks Extend Gain as Dow Advances 5.98
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices extended their gains yesterday, and the Dow Jones industrial average advanced 5.98 points, to 2,753.63.

headline: U.S. Protests TV Limits
abstract: LEAD: The United States formally challenged today a rule set by the European Community that puts informal limits on the amount of non-European-made programs that member nations may broadcast on their television stations.

headline: Salvadoran Rift: Church vs. Oligarchy
abstract: LEAD: When Pope Paul VI named Oscar Arnulfo Romero as the senior prelate in this country in 1977, the wealthy and powerful gave thanks, contributing generously to pay for a consecration ceremony that set a new standard for lavishness.

headline: Mitsubishi Estate a Force In Japanese Real Estate
abstract: LEAD: When the brokers and investment bankers representing the Rockefeller Group went looking for a buyer with the cachet to match that of their prestigious client, they did not have to look far.

headline: Battle for Avon Intensifies As Basses Disclose 6% Stake
abstract: LEAD: A new development in the takeover battle for Avon Products Inc. emerged yesterday as a group led by Robert M. Bass, the Texas businessman, announced that it owned nearly 6 percent of the cosmetics company and might hold talks with Avon's top management.

headline: Communists Warning Warsaw Over Change
abstract: LEAD: The Communist Party warned the Solidarity-led Government today that it lacked a popular mandate for its sweeping plans to switch Poland to a free-market economy.

headline: Patents; Sewage Sludge Used To Make Bricks and Tile
abstract: LEAD: The Fujimi Tile Company of Nagoya, Japan, has patented a method for making ceramic bricks and tile out of sewage sludge. The process begins by burning the sludge into ash and then mixing the ash with ceramic raw materials, including debris from making conventional tiles, to form a clay that can be molded and baked.

headline: Gypsy Protesters Driven From a Nazi Camp
abstract: LEAD: Gypsies who had occupied a former concentration camp for a month to dramatize their campaign to remain in West Germany were driven out by the police this week in an action that highlighted a troubling aspect of West Germany's immigration policies.

headline: Salvador Rebels Mount Attacks Across the Capital
abstract: LEAD: Guerrillas carried out a wave of attacks throughout the capital today, killing two children and injuring at least eight other people, officials and witnesses said.  [ The residence of President Alfredo Cristiani was among the targets attacked by the rebels, Reuters reported, quoting radio reports. Two policemen were wounded by gunfire at Mr.

headline: Interest Reported In Hershey Oil
abstract: LEAD: The Transamerica Corporation said undisclosed third parties had got in touch with it about purchasing its 26.4 percent stake in the Hershey Oil Corporation. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Transamerica said it had held preliminary discussions with one group and might hold further talks.

headline: Aquino Approves a Measure Granting Emergency Powers
abstract: LEAD: President Corazon C. Aquino signed a bill today granting her emergency powers and said she would use them to protect the country and revive the economy after this month's military revolt.

headline: Lebanese Greet U.S. Envoy As He Backs New President
abstract: LEAD: Thousands of Lebanese gave a festive welcome today to the United States Ambassador to Lebanon, John McCarthy, as he formally presented his credentials to Lebanon's new President and handed the Lebanese leader a letter of support from President Bush.

headline: SOVIETS REDUCING ARMS FOR MANAGUA
abstract: LEAD: After a decade as the largest supplier of weapons for the Sandinista army, the Soviet Union now appears committed to reducing its military aid to Nicaragua in order to strengthen its relations with Washington, diplomats here say.

headline: Higher Interest Rates Seem Likely
abstract: LEAD: Interest rates could be pushed a bit higher over the next few weeks because of an avalanche of new Treasury securities and a growing sense among market participants that the Federal Reserve Board may not move quickly to ease monetary policy, credit analysts contend.

headline: Iran Responds in Kind to 'Bullying' by U.S.
abstract: LEAD: Parliament approved a bill today allowing Iran to arrest any American anywhere who offends it.

headline: Chile Plans to Create Strong Central Bank
abstract: LEAD: As it prepares to turn over power to elected civilians, the Government of Gen. Augusto Pinochet is creating an autonomous central bank that it says will help preserve Chile's hard-won economic stability, growth and modernization.

headline: Poland Says Germans Get Right to Go West
abstract: LEAD: East Germany has agreed to allow almost 1,000 of its citizens who have taken refuge in Poland to emigrate to the country of their choice, Poland said today.

headline: Argentina and Britain Opening Consular Ties
abstract: LEAD: Ending three days of talks here, Argentina and Britain decided today to resume consular ties and direct air and sea links, clearing the path for substantial normalization of relations, according to a joint statement issued today at the end of three days of talks.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Heller Breene Sold by WCRS
abstract: LEAD: The WCRS Group has solved the problem of what to do about Heller Breene Advertising, its Boston ad agency that was sent reeling eight weeks ago when Heller's co-founder left for another agency: it sold the company. The buyer is Cipriani

headline: Talking Deals; How T.V.A. Got Big Refinancing
abstract: LEAD: AFTER a 15-year absence from the public debt markets, the Tennessee Valley Authority will announce today that it plans to offer about $3 billion in bonds next week as the initial phase of a $6.7 billion refinancing, T.V.A. executives said yesterday.

headline: Former Fingerhut Chief Will Return to His Post
abstract: LEAD: The Primerica Corporation said yesterday that its mail order subisidiary, the Fingerhut Companies, would be headed once more by Ted Deikel, who guided the company to its original success.

headline: Railroad in Angola to Be Revived
abstract: LEAD: In a move that reflects growing confidence in Angola's economic future, Belgian engineers are preparing to reopen the war-torn Benguela railroad, once the main artery into Central Africa's rich mineral reserves.

headline: Tokyo Firm Is Punished
abstract: LEAD: The Daiwa Securities Company of Tokyo has been punished for compensating a customer for losses in stock transactions, a company official said Tuesday. The official said the company had not violated any laws, but he quoted Masahiro Dozen, Daiwa's president, as apologizing for unfairness to other investors.

headline: Eastern and AMR Resume Talks
abstract: LEAD: Eastern Airlines has resumed talks with the AMR Corporation, parent of American Airlines, about selling Eastern's Latin American routes and other assets.

headline: Limits on Death
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: U.N. Official Assails Curbs on Aid to Afghans
abstract: LEAD: The United Nations official in charge of coordinating supplies of aid for Afghanistan expressed concern today that the United States and other countries are withholding donations in order to weaken the Soviet-backed Government in Kabul.

headline: East German Television Lightens Up, a Bit
abstract: LEAD: A kind of glasnost appeared on the country's two tightly controlled television channels today, a day after Erich Honecker's fall as leader of East Germany.

headline: Raleigh, N.C., Paper Closing
abstract: LEAD: The Raleigh Times, the evening sister paper in North Carolina's capital to the morning News and Observer, is ceasing publication on Nov. 30 after 110 years.

headline: Supermarket Merger Deal
abstract: LEAD: The California State Attorney General, John Van de Kamp, announced an agreement today with American Stores to modify a court order blocking the merger of the Alpha Beta and Lucky grocery store chains while he pursues an antitrust challenge to the merger. The United States Supreme Court agreed last month to hear that challenge.

headline: Dow Rises 7.04 as Light Trading Continues
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices rose moderately yesterday, with the Dow Jones industrial average closing above 2,700, after languishing in a slightly higher range throughout most of the session.

headline: Upheaval in the East; Bulgaria's Communist Chief Plans To Relax Grip and Hold Elections
abstract: LEAD: Yielding to popular demands for more democracy, Bulgaria's new leader said today that the Communist Party's monopoly on power should be abandoned and that free parliamentary elections should be held by next spring.

headline: Upheaval in the East: The Baltics; GORBACHEV AGREES TO GO TO LITHUANIA ON SECESSION MOVE
abstract: LEAD: President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has decided to go to Lithuania soon to consult with rank-and-file Communist Party members about the Lithuanian party's decision to break from Moscow, several people who attended an emergency party meeting here said today. The two-day meeting of the national party leadership ended without agreement on how to address the problem.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; 3 Executives Honored
abstract: LEAD: The Advertising Hall of Fame announced the election of three new members, who will be inducted on March 28. They are James E. Burke, former chairman and chief executive of Johnson & Johnson; Raymond O. Mithun, co-founder of what is now the Campbell-Mithun-Esty agency, and Jean Wade Rindlaub, former director and group copy head of BBDO, who wrote the ''Back home for keeps .

headline: Treasury Notes and Bonds Rise
abstract: LEAD: Investors bid up the prices of Treasury notes and bonds yesterday as the stock market weakened.

headline: Lebanon Cabinet Talks Begin Despite Protest by Christians
abstract: LEAD: Lebanon's new President, Rene Moawad, started consultations today on the selection of a Cabinet to serve as a ''government of national entente,'' but his rival, Gen. Michel Aoun, gave no sign that he was ready to relinquish power.

headline: Swiss Bank In U.S. Link
abstract: LEAD: The Swiss Bank Corporation of Zurich is joining forces with O'Connor & Associates of Chicago, the leading trader of financial options in the United States, the two companies announced yesterday.

headline: PEACE EFFORTS ARE SET BACK
abstract: LEAD: The new Lebanese President, Rene Moawad, was assassinated today when a huge bomb blew up his car. He died after only 17 days in office.

headline: Bombing at Salvadoran Leftists' Office Kills Eight
abstract: LEAD: Eight people, including one of El Salvador's most outspoken leftist organizers, were killed today and 35 others injured when a bomb exploded in the headquarters of a labor confederation here.

headline: Government That Exiled Him Hurries to Mourn Sakharov
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Government, which once exiled Andrei D. Sakharov for being a human rights champion, today embraced him in death. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev mourned the national loss of ''a man of conviction and sincerity.''

headline: In a City Huddling in Terror, Food Runs Out as Bullets Fly
abstract: LEAD: Rosa and her two daughters have stayed huddled in their small apartment here for three days.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; CMS Chief to Weigh Conversion of Shoreham
abstract: LEAD: If James W. Cook has his way, he could be calling the shots on the conversion of the Shoreham nuclear power plant to one that uses natural gas.

headline: Video Sales Gaining on Rentals
abstract: LEAD: On Nov. 15 Warner Brothers' summer hit, ''Batman,'' will go on sale in stores across the country, and the price will not be $89.95, as such a newly released film might have sold for in years past, but $24.98.

headline: Honduras Votes for a Leader To Tread Between Two Wars
abstract: LEAD: Voters in this nation stuck between two civil wars voted today for a president who will have to deal with the sticky questions of how to get rid of thousands of Nicaraguan rebels and what to do with half a million war refugees.

headline: Treasury Selling Bills Today and Thursday
abstract: LEAD: The Treasury's schedule of issues this week is confined to the bill market, beginning with today's regular weekly auction of three- and six-month bills. On Thursday the Treasury will also have an auction of one-year bills.

headline: More Traders Subpoenaed
abstract: LEAD: Federal agents delivered subpoenas to eight more futures traders this week, defense lawyers said today. The lawyers said traders from the Chicago Mercantile Exchange's Standard & Poor's 500-stock index futures pit were the targets of the latest step in the investigation of the Chicago futures exchanges.

headline: Delta to Expand Atlanta Operation
abstract: LEAD: Delta Air Lines said it plans a big expansion of its operations at Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport with financing from $347.9 million in tax-exempt bonds issued by the city.

headline: Economic Scene; Another Autumn Of Fiscal Discord
abstract: LEAD: WITH the new fiscal year 1990 under way, and the United States operating without a Federal budget, economic battles are raging in Washington from Capitol Hill to the White House to Constitution Avenue.

headline: The U.N. Today
abstract: LEAD:  General Assembly  Meets at 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.  POLITICAL AND SECURITY COMMITTEE - 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.  SPECIAL POLITICAL COMMITTEE - 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.  SOCIAL, HUMANITARIAN AND CULTURAL COMMITTEE - 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.  ADMINISTRATIVE AND BUDGETARY COMMITTEE - 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.

headline: Noriega Reportedly Orders Executions of Coup Figures
abstract: LEAD: Moments after putting down a violent coup attempt last Tuesday, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega exploded in rage against his captured opponents and ordered the immediate execution of several rebel officers, including a close friend who was the coup leader, diplomats here said today.

headline: ADMITS BREAKING ARMS PACT
abstract: LEAD: Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told the Soviet legislature today that the nine-year Soviet military role in Afghanistan had violated Soviet law and international norms of behavior.

headline: Houghton Mifflin Will Buy Gollancz, British Publisher
abstract: LEAD: The Houghton Mifflin Company, one of the few remaining independent American book publishers, announced yesterday that it intends to purchase Victor Gollancz, a 60-year-old privately held British publishing house. Terms of the deal were not disclosed.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Volvic still water, a unit of the Perrier Group, to Lord Einstein O'Neill & Partners. Budget has not been set.

headline: Cray Cutting Its Computer Work Force
abstract: LEAD: Citing advances in manufacturing technology and the switch to a more advanced supercomputer model, Cray Research Inc., said yesterday that it planned to lay off about 400 of its assembly workers, about 7 percent of its 5,400 workers worldwide.

headline: China's Credit Rating Downgraded by Moody's
abstract: LEAD: Signaling uncertainty about China's political stability, Moody's Investors Service Inc. today downgraded the country's long-term credit rating.

headline: Anger With Ortega Unites Policy Makers in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: Bush Administration officials and members of Congress from both parties condemned President Daniel Ortega Saavedra of Nicaragua today for his decision to end a 19-month cease-fire with Nicaraguan guerrillas supported by the United States.

headline: ITALY COMMUNISTS WILL CHANGE NAME
abstract: LEAD: Swept by the tornado of events in Eastern Europe, the Italian Communist Party, largest in the West, has formally decided to change its name and its identity, down to the hammer-and-sickle emblem.

headline: Sutton Holding Bids for DeSoto
abstract: LEAD: DeSoto Inc., a paint company based in Des Plaines, Ill., received a takeover offer of $50 a share in cash from the Sutton Holding Corporation, a New York concern owned by investors and led by William Spier and Michael Zurawin. Sutton, which said it would begin a tender offer within five business days, already owns about 14.6 percent of D

headline: Upheaval in the East: The Scene; Gunfire and Confusion Temper a City's Elation
abstract: LEAD: Armed skirmishes between Government troops and the security police swirled today across this city that had led the revolution against the deposed Rumanian leader, Nicolae Ceausescu.

headline: PAKISTAN WEARIES OF AFGHAN BURDEN
abstract: LEAD: The Government of Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto is growing increasingly impatient with the burden of supporting the Muslim guerrillas who use Pakistan as a base for their operations against the Soviet-backed Afghan Government.

headline: Police Storm Brazil Prison
abstract: LEAD: State troopers stormed a prison in southern Brazil today and ended a siege by inmates, killing 8 prisoners and freeing 39 hostages, the police said. Fifty troopers rushed into the Curitiba prison firing their guns after prisoners killed one hostage and wounded three others, said Sgt. Ericu Gilberto Cassou Miller.

headline: C.I.A. Seeks Looser Rules On Killings During Coups
abstract: LEAD: William H. Webster, the Director of Central Intelligence, called today on the President and Congress to consider giving the Central Intelligence Agency greater latitude in supporting potentially violent efforts to overthrow foreign dictators.

headline: Program Trading Is Not the Culprit
abstract: LEAD: Program trading bashing has become as fashionable today as attacking Communists was during the McCarthy era. Ban program trading -or so the argument goes - and stock market volatility will dissappear, the Dow Jones Industrial Average will stabilize and the small investor will return to the market.

headline: Arafat Sends Bush a Message on Talks With Israel
abstract: LEAD: Yasir Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, has sent a message to President Bush expressing a willingness to negotiate peace with Israel, Administration officials said today.

headline: At the Book Fair, a Hot Story Is the Takeovers
abstract: LEAD: A prime topic of conversation at this year's Frankfurt Book Fair, publishing's biggest and most important annual event, is not authors and books, but mergers and acquisitions.

headline: Talking Deals; When Size Lead Is No Advantage
abstract: LEAD: THE market leader usually has the competitive edge. But when it comes to mergers and acquisitions, it may be advantageous to be the No. 2 or No. 3 player, two recent cases suggest.

headline: A Potential New Soviet Export Product: Cold-War-Surplus Missiles
abstract: LEAD: In an effort to turn swords into plowshares, or ''tanks into tractors,'' as Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d put it last week, the Soviet Union is trying to turn its SS-20 missile into a commercial rocket for launching small satellites into space.

headline: NEWS SUMMARY
abstract: LEAD:  INTERNATIONAL A3-21  The Soviet Communists' monopoly on politics and power is not an issue open for debate, President Mikhail Gorbachev said, quickly settling the question during the oecond session of the National Congress. Page A1

headline: S.E.C. Acts To Smooth Trading
abstract: LEAD: In an effort to smooth the big swings that have plagued the stock market because of computerized trading techniques, the Securities and Exchange Commission yesterday approved for trading a new financial instrument that would allow investors to buy and sell a ''basket'' of 500 stocks in a single order on the New York Stock Exchange.

headline: Czechoslovakia: A History of Tumult
abstract: LEAD: Oct. 28, 1918: With the collapse of the Austro-Hungarian Empire in World War I, the independence of the Czechoslovak state is proclaimed; the following month, Tomas G. Masaryk, the Czechoslovak nationalist leader, is elected the country's first President.

headline: Market Place; Why Japan Likes Lower U.S. Rates
abstract: LEAD:  FOR most of 1989, the Japanese stock market has been a laggard, a sharp reversal from the leading role it played for much of the 1980's. But it was Japan that stemmed the tide of the mini-crash that rocked most world markets in mid-October, and this week it was Japan that reacted most enthusiastically when the Federal

headline: STRAINED U.S. TIES REPORTED IN CHINA
abstract: LEAD: A secret analysis prepared for the Chinese leadership says that China's relationship with the United States has deteriorated sharply and will continue to be rocked by new conflicts, but that President Bush is quietly trying to limit the damage.

headline: UPHEAVAL IN THE EAST: Overview; CEAUSESCU FLEES A REVOLT IN RUMANIA BUT DIVIDED SECURITY FORCES FIGHT ON
abstract: LEAD: After ruling Rumania as a dictator for a quarter of a century, President Nicolae Ceausescu was forced to flee Bucharest Friday when angry crowds of anti-Government demonstrators, backed by army units, took over large sections of the capital.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Arby's 42 largest franchisees formed a group, A. P. Association Inc., to oppose the continued control of the roast-beef sandwich chain by Victor Posner, chairman of DWG Corp., which controls Arby's.

headline: Economic Scene; Foreign Owners For U.S. Airlines?
abstract: LEAD: FIRST there were Pan Am and T.W.A. and United and American. And now - Discovery?

headline: C.F.T.C. Bars Restitution Bid
abstract: LEAD: Federal futures regulators voted down a proposal today that would have allowed them to force dishonest brokers and traders to pay restitution to the customers they had cheated.

headline: More Than 50 Burn to Death In a 2-Bus Accident in Sudan
abstract: LEAD: A bus veered into a high-voltage power pole and caught fire after colliding with another bus on Friday, and more than 50 people burned to death, the authorities said today.

headline: Unfinished Business With Canada
abstract: LEAD: Nine months after the United States-Canada free-trade agreement began chipping away at tariffs and trade barriers, trade relations between the world's two busiest trading partners have slipped once again to their accustomed place on the policy makers' back burner.

headline: Survey Finds Americans Favor a Reunited Germany
abstract: LEAD: The upheaval in Eastern Europe has left Americans optimistic and ready for even greater change in the region. Two out of three say East and West Germany should be reunited, and an equal number predict that Eastern Europe will be largely out of Soviet control a year from now.

headline: Small Shop Benefits From A Big Client
abstract: LEAD: SLATER HANFT MARTIN is a small advertising agency that is every large agency's nightmare.

headline: As Profits Slide, a Struggle to Survive
abstract: LEAD: These are tough times for the nation's $303 billion a year business of selling automobiles.

headline: Dividend Meetings
abstract: LEAD: Following is a partial list of dividend meetings for the week of Oct. 30, 1989:  MONDAY  Armstrong World Inds  Boeing Co  Consldtd Freightways  Foster Wheeler  Foxboro Co  Union Camp Corp  Wackenhut Corp  TUESDAY  Airborne Freight  American Brands  Borden Inc  Duke Power Co  Inspiration Res  Koger Pptys  Standex Intl  UGI Corp  USX Co  Warner Lambert

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; People
abstract: LEAD: * Robert R. Russo has been named president of LSGE Direct, a division of LSGE Marketing/Communications of Avon, Conn.

headline: Gasoline Prices Drop
abstract: LEAD: The average price of gasoline nationwide dipped about a half-cent a gallon at the pumps in the last two weeks. The Lundberg Survey of 12,000 gas stations showed the average retail price of all grades of gasoline, including taxes, at 109.12 cents a gallon on Friday, down 0.53 cent from Oct. 6, Trilby Lundberg said Sunday.

headline: Poland's Hard Times Deepen, Dampening Hope for Change
abstract: LEAD: Among the Poles who gathered today in Mokotowska street for a plate of soup and some bread was an 83-year old retired schoolteacher named Maria, visibly uncomfortable with the rough-and-tumble atmosphere.

headline: New S.E.C. Chief Defines Goals
abstract: LEAD: In his first public discussion of the future policy of the Securities and Exchange Commission since he took office as chairman two weeks ago, Richard C. Breeden sent reassuring signals to the markets today, saying that his agency would not press Congress to grant the commission power to close the nation's securities markets in times of crisis.

headline: Ciba-Corning Deal
abstract: LEAD: Ciba-Geigy A.G. said it had agreed to buy Corning Inc.'s share of the Ciba-Corning Diagnostics Corporation, a joint venture in which each company had owned half. Terms were not disclosed. Ciba-Corning, based in Medfield, Mass., provides diagnostic systems and related products. It has 2,500 employees and had 1988 sales of about $300 million.

headline: Earnings of Japanese
abstract: LEAD: The average employee of a Japanese company earned $27,000 last year, but on average, a man earned more than twice as much as a woman, according to a Government study. The average annual income for Japan's 38 million corporate employees, including bonuses, was up by $915, or 3.5 percent, from the previous year, the National Tax Agency said Saturday.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Omnicom Sells Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Omnicom Group said yesterday that it had sold a subsidiary, Franklin Spier Inc., to the agency's senior management and a group of investors. Omnicom did not disclose the terms of the deal. Alix Nelson, the chairman of Franklin Spier, which specializes in advertising for publishing houses, said Omnicom's emphasis on global marketing services did not suit its local focus and client list.

headline: Sallie Mae Prices $500 Million Notes
abstract: LEAD: The Student Loan Marketing Association, known as Sallie Mae, priced $500 million of short-term floating-rate notes in its regular monthly issue.

headline: Account of Plot: Close Call for Noriega
abstract: LEAD: Conspirators who tried to overthrow Gen. Antonio Manuel Noriega on Tuesday planned to trap him in his office and turn him over to United States authorities, a businessman with close ties to the Panamanian armed forces said today.

headline: Mexican Drug Leaders Guilty In the Killing of a U.S. Agent
abstract: LEAD: Two of Mexico's most powerful drug traffickers were found guilty today of the 1985 murder of a Federal drug agent from the United States. Each was sentenced to a prison term of more than 100 years, and millions of dollars in personal property was ordered seized.

headline: Tokyo Stocks Regain Some of Early Losses
abstract: LEAD: In the first international response to the steep stock market tumble in New York on Friday, prices fell sharply in light trading today at the opening of trading here, but by the end of the morning session they recouped about a third of their initial losses.

headline: Aide to Gorbachev Takes Pravda Helm; Brezhnev Man Is Out
abstract: LEAD: The chief editor of Pravda, the stodgy and authoritative organ of mainstream Soviet Communism, was removed from his job today and replaced by a close aide to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.

headline: Destiny in Air, Leaders Arrive For the Summit
abstract: LEAD: President Bush and President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union arrived today on this Mediterranean island for a summit conference beginning on Saturday during which both hope to start the search for a new world order.

headline: ACTIVE P.L.O. ROLE SOUGHT FOR TALKS
abstract: LEAD: As the newest effort to resolve the Palestinian-Israeli conflict slides into familiar patterns of ambiguity, the Palestine Liberation Organization is balking at the role of invisible player assigned to it by Egypt, a principal Arab backer.

headline: Frank Mankiewicz To Advise Hungarians
abstract: LEAD: Frank Mankiewicz, a top adviser to Robert F. Kennedy and George S. McGovern in their Democratic Presidential campaigns, appears to be ready to engage in another dramatic political battle, one on behalf of Hungary's Socialist Party, which until October called itself the Communist Party.

headline: Philippine Debt Is Rescheduled
abstract: LEAD: The Philippines and the United States have agreed to reschedule payments on $362.2 million of Manila's debt, the Philippine Finance Secretary, Vicente Jayme, said Sunday.

headline: Gerber to Close Plant in Ontario
abstract: LEAD: The Gerber Products Company said it will close its Niagara Falls, Ontario, plant by April, terminating about 150 jobs. The world's largest maker of baby food is consolidating production in its three United States plants: in Fremont, Mich.; Fort Smith, Ark., and Asheville, N.C.

headline: Car Sales Off, With Big 3 Hurt the Most
abstract: LEAD: Sales of domestically produced cars and trucks fell in late November and were down sharply at the Big Three. Japan's auto makers, however, continued to show relative strength.

headline: U.S. Rebuffs Trade Critics
abstract: LEAD: The United States hit back today at critics of the unilateral action it has taken on trade issues, saying others did the same and should not pass judgment.

headline: P.L.O. Tries to Block Spread of Lebanese Fighting
abstract: LEAD: Guerrillas of the Palestine Liberation Organization took up combat positions in southern Lebanon today to prevent eight days of fighting between rival Shiite militiamen from spilling into areas under Palestinian control.

headline: Dry Dock Lays Off 24 in Real Estate
abstract: LEAD: The Dollar Dry Dock Bank said it laid off 24 people last week in its residential real estate lending department because of the slow pace of home sales. Robert H. Steele, Dollar Dry Dock's chairman, said originations of new mortgage loans had been running 60 percent below the bank's projections.

headline: Cable Giant Hungry for Programs
abstract: LEAD: With 11 million subscribers and interests in more than a dozen program distribution services, Tele-Communications Inc. is already the nation's largest cable television operator, a behemoth in its business. But for its president, John C. Malone, that is no longer enough. Like other cable operators, his company is stepping up expansion with an eye on becoming a program producer as well.

headline: Amex Details Options Plan
abstract: LEAD: Despite objections from some of its rivals, the American Stock Exchange is moving to put into effect a plan that allows stock options to be traded on more than one exchange.

headline: Protest Rallies Resume in Prague In Effort to Oust New Government
abstract: LEAD: About 200,000 people poured into Wenceslas Square today to shout their rejection of a new Government formed on Sunday and to applaud a call for a general strike next Monday if it is not replaced.

headline: Brokerages To Clients: Stay Calm
abstract: LEAD: Major brokerages as well as smaller money-management firms did their best yesterday to reassure their clients that the stock market would weather the current storm on Wall Street.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Badger Co., Cambridge, Mass., an engineering and construction subsidary of Raytheon Co., appointed Lazzaro G. Modigliani president and chief executive.

headline: Japan Export Bank Offers 8.35% Notes
abstract: LEAD: The Export-Import Bank of Japan is offering $150 million in 8.35 percent guaranteed notes due in 1999 at a price of 100 through underwriters led by the First Boston Corporation.

headline: Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Catskill Association of Tourism Services to Lipman, Richmond, Greene.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Alcan Aluminium Ltd., Montreal, a maker of aluminum and aluminum products, received approval from the Toronto and Montreal stock exchanges to buy back 15 million of its own common shares, or about 6.5 percent of the shares outstanding. Purchases will be made starting Friday.

headline: Trading Begins in Stock 'Baskets'
abstract: LEAD: Trading in stock ''baskets'' began yesterday in New York and Chicago, marred by a computer problem in New York that led to two basket trades being canceled. The new product, approved by the Securities and Exchange Commission on Wednesday, allows investors to buy or sell all the stocks in the Standard &

headline: Quake Conditions in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: The geological conditions that produced yesterday's earthquake north of Sydney, Australia, are strikingly similar to those on the East Coast of the United States, according to specialists in earthquake hazards.

headline: 'Junk Bond' Rally Continues But New Issues Are Lacking
abstract: LEAD: Prices of ''junk bonds'' rose again yesterday, and even though the market's rally entered its fourth day, underwriters of high-yield bonds said the improvement was not great enough to reschedule the bond offerings that were postponed last month.

headline: U.S. Tells of Its Concern About Olivetti
abstract: LEAD: President Bush told the President of Italy today that the United States was concerned that an Italian company might have sold technology for a supersonic jetfighter to the Soviet Union, officials said.

headline: B. Altman Bid Deadline
abstract: LEAD: The L. J. Hooker Company, whose parent, the Hooker Corporation of Australia, is in Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings, filed a petition with the bankruptcy court yesterday for a deadline of next Friday to consider bids for its seven B. Altman & Company stores. Hooker is also seeking to liquidate B.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Family Circle Magazine Names a New Publisher
abstract: LEAD: Winthrop Stevens was named yesterday as publisher of Family Circle magazine. He succeeds Charles H. Townsend, who remains president and chief operating officer.

headline: Eastern Talks With Pilots Set
abstract: LEAD: Eastern Airlines said today that it set a special meeting with its pilots' union for Tuesday to eliminate any uncertainties about employee status.

headline: U.S. Issues Mixed in Slow Trading
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury securities were very narrowly mixed in dull trading yesterday, as dealers effectively closed their books on 1989.

headline: U.S. Troops Entered Envoy's Residence, Nicaragua Charges
abstract: LEAD: Nicaragua's Ambassador to Panama said United States troops searched his residence on Friday, and the Nicaraguan Government responded by ordering 120 American diplomats and embassy workers to leave Nicaragua.
